{"title_page": "Steve Stockman", "text_new": "{{short description|American politician from Texas}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Steve Stockman\n|image        = SteveStockmanCP.jpg\n|state        = [[Texas]]\n|district     = {{ushr|Texas|36|36th}}\n|term_start   = January 3, 2013\n|term_end     = January 3, 2015\n|predecessor  = ''Constituency established''\n|successor    = [[Brian Babin]]\n|state1       = [[Texas]]\n|district1    = {{ushr|Texas|9|9th}}\n|term_start1  = January 3, 1995\n|term_end1    = January 3, 1997\n|predecessor1 = [[Jack Brooks (American politician)|Jack Brooks]]\n|successor1   = [[Nick Lampson]]\n|birthname    = Stephen Ernest Stockman\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1956|11|14}}\n|birth_place  = [[Bloomfield Hills, Michigan|Bloomfield Hills]], [[Michigan]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n|death_date   =\n|death_place  =\n|nationality  = American\n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse       = Patti Ferguson (1988\u2013present)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.texasmarriagerecords.org/marriage-of-stephen-stockman-and-patti-ferguson.html|title=Stephen Stockman and Patti Ferguson, Married December 10, 1988|publisher=texasmarriagerecords.org|accessdate=August 2, 2012}}</ref>\n|alma_mater   = [[University of Houston\u2013Clear Lake|University of Houston, Clear Lake]]}}\n'''Stephen Ernest Stockman''' (born November 14, 1956) is an [[United States|American]] politician who is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] and a convicted felon. He served as the U.S. Representative for [[Texas's 9th congressional district]] from 1995 to 1997 and for [[Texas's 36th congressional district]] from 2013 to 2015. Stockman ran in the Republican primary for the [[United States Senate]] [[United States Senate election in Texas, 2014|in the 2014 election]] but lost  to incumbent Senator [[John Cornyn]].\n\n==Early life, education, and business career==\nStockman was born in [[Bloomfield Hills, Michigan|Bloomfield Hills]], [[Michigan]], outside [[Detroit]]. His parents were evangelistic Christian teachers.<ref name=Clueless/> He graduated from [[Dondero High School]] in [[Royal Oak, Michigan|Royal Oak]], Michigan. From 1985 to 1986, he attended [[San Jacinto College]] but dropped out because he suffered from what he called \"partying syndrome\". In 1977 as Stockman was reporting to jail for traffic tickets, the jailers found [[valium]] in his possession after his girlfriend allegedly hid some in his underwear. He was charged with felony possession of a controlled substance, but the charge was later dropped.<ref name=Swartz>{{cite journal|author=Mimi Swartz |title=Congressman Clueless |journal=Texas Monthly |date=February 1996 |url=http://www.texasmonthly.com/story/congressman-clueless/page/0/2}}</ref><ref name=Gillman>{{cite news|last=Gillman|first=Todd|title=In 1995, Stockman admitted jail time, felony charge. Today he denies that, accusing Cornyn allies of lying.|url=http://trailblazersblog.dallasnews.com/2014/01/in-1995-stockman-admitted-jail-time-felony-charge-today-he-denies-that-accusing-cornyn-allies-of-lying.html/|newspaper=Dallas Morning News|accessdate=1 February 2014}}</ref> He later became a [[Born again (Christianity)|born-again Christian]].<ref name=\"johngizzi\">John Gizzi, [http://www.humanevents.com/2012/07/07/steve-stockman-vies-for-36th-texas-district-seat/ Steve Stockman Vies for 36th Texas District Seat], ''[[Human Events]]'', July 7, 2012</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Christopher Hooks |title=Steve Stockman Can't Lose |date=December 20, 2013 |journal=Politico |url=http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2013/12/steve-stockman-john-cornyn-texas-senate-republican-primary-101412.html?hp=t1}}</ref> In 1990, he earned a bachelor's degree in [[accounting]] from the [[University of Houston\u2013Clear Lake]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Salesman, 33, to run for Brooks seat|newspaper=Houston Chronicle|date=December 20, 1989|page=26}}</ref>  He worked as a computer salesman in [[Friendswood, Texas]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Local candidates rush to replace outgoing incumbents|newspaper=Houston Chronicle|date=March 11, 1990|author=Alan Bernstein}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives (1995\u20131997)==\n===Elections===\n;1990\nStockman's first run for Congress was in March 1990 in [[Texas's 9th congressional district]].  The district, anchored by [[Beaumont, Texas|Beaumont]] and [[Galveston, Texas|Galveston]], had been represented by [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] [[Jack Brooks (American politician)|Representative Jack Brooks]] since 1953.  His primary challenger was Mayor Maury Meyers of [[Beaumont, Texas|Beaumont]].<ref name=brookswins>{{cite news|title=Primaries '90 \u2013 Rep. Brooks wins Dem contest; Meyers leads GOP opponent|newspaper=Houston Chronicle|date=March 15, 1990|author=Richard Stewart}}</ref> [[Oliver North]] made appearances at two of Stockman's fundraisers.<ref>{{cite news|title=Iran-contra figure North appears at Hance fund-raisers|newspaper=[[Dallas Morning News]]|date=February 3, 1990|author=Sam Attlesey|quote=In addition to the fee he received for appearing with Mr. Hance, Mr. North also will receive $25,000 for joining Republican congressional candidate Steve Stockman on Saturday in Beaumont and Houston.}}</ref>\n\nMeyers got 44.3% of the primary vote; Stockman, 41%.<ref name=brookswins/>  Since no candidate had a majority, there was a runoff election and, with the support of third-place finisher Steve Clifford,<ref name=loser>{{cite news|title=Loser backs Meyers in runoff|newspaper=Houston Chronicle|date=March 16, 1990|page=A25}}</ref> Meyers beat Stockman to win the Republican nomination.<ref>{{cite news|title=Shine gets GOP nod in race for Congress|newspaper=Austin American-Statesman|date=April 11, 1990|author1=Mike Ward|author2=Drew Parma|page=A9}}</ref>\n\n;1992\nStockman ran again in 1992 for the House in District 9. This time he was unopposed in the primary.<ref>{{cite news|title=Unopposed Republican candidates|newspaper=Houston Chronicle|date=March 1, 1992|page=15|section=Voter's Guide}}</ref>  The [[1992 Republican National Convention]] was held in Houston in August of that year. Stockman organized a \"congressional cruise\" on the [[Houston Ship Channel]] as a fundraising opportunity, but no members of Congress attended.<ref>{{cite news|title=National convention continues to have ripple effect locally|newspaper=Houston Chronicle|date=August 23, 1992|author=Alan Bernstein|page=C2}}</ref> Democrat Brooks defeated him 56% to 44%.<ref>{{cite news|title=House of Representatives [Part 2 of 2]|newspaper=Sacramento Bee|date=November 5, 1992|page=A16}}</ref>\n\n;1994\nStockman ran again for House District 9 in 1994. He had two challengers in the Republican primary: John LeCour and James Milburn.  Stockman finished the primary with a [[Landslide victory|landslide]] 74%.<ref>{{cite news|title=Election '94/Bentsen, Clark in runoff/District 25 victor to face Fontenot|newspaper=Houston Chronicle|date=March 9, 1994|author=Susan Warren}}</ref>\n\nHis Democratic opponent in the general election was, as before, incumbent Jack Brooks.  Initially the [[National Rifle Association]] (NRA) endorsed Brooks and even donated $5,000 to his cause, while the [[Gun Owners of America]] endorsed Stockman.<ref name=tenure>{{cite news|title=Rep. Brooks' long tenure in danger \u2013 The crime bill, his incumbency may sink the Democrat's bid for a 22nd term|newspaper=Austin American-Statesman|date=October 22, 1994|page=A13}}</ref>  However, a number of NRA members threatened to resign from the organization over the issue and the NRA withdrew their support for Brooks, remaining neutral in the race.<ref name=tenure/>  In a major upset, Stockman beat Brooks, who, had he won, would have become [[Dean of the United States House of Representatives]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Texan in line as House dean \u2013 Jack Brooks has reputation as in-your-face politician|newspaper=Fort Worth Star-Telegram|date=July 25, 1994|author=Ron Hutcheson|page=1}}</ref> by 51% to 49%.<ref>{{cite news|title=State Results|newspaper=Austin American-Statesman|date=November 9, 1994|page=A8}}</ref>\n\n;1996\nStockman ran unopposed in the 1996 Republican primary.<ref>{{cite news|title=Unopposed Republicans|newspaper=Houston Chronicle|date=March 3, 1996|page=16|section=Voter's Guide}}</ref>  In July a federal court ordered the boundaries of 13 Texas House districts to be redrawn because of racial [[gerrymandering]], although Stockman's district was barely affected.<ref>{{cite news|title=The shape of things to come/Judges shift district lines/New races ordered this year for seats in Houston, Dallas|newspaper=Houston Chronicle|date=August 7, 1996|author=Alan Bernstein|quote=9th District:Few changes made; first-term conservative still running in a majority Democratic and Anglo district stretching from Galveston to Beaumont.}}</ref>  Stockman won a [[Plurality (voting)|plurality]] in the November election with 46%, forcing a runoff against Democratic [[Jefferson County, Texas|Jefferson County]] assessor [[Nick Lampson]] in the runoff election.<ref>{{cite news|title=ELECTION '96/Stockman-Lampson runoff brawl may take place on national stage|newspaper=Houston Chronicle|date=November 7, 1996|page=34|author=Richard Stewart}}</ref>  Lampson won the runoff election with 53% of the vote<ref>{{cite news|title=Lampson, Brady, Bentsen win House seats in runoff election|newspaper=Austin American-Statesman|date=December 11, 1996|author=Michael Graczyk|page=A10}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nDuring his 1995 term, Stockman opposed the [[1994 economic crisis in Mexico|U.S. bailout of the Mexican peso]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Sangillo|first=Gregg|title=Texas, 36th House District|url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/congress-legacy/texas-36th-house-district-20121101|access-date=February 13, 2013|newspaper=National Journal|date=November 1, 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130130174630/http://www.nationaljournal.com/congress-legacy/texas-36th-house-district-20121101|archive-date=January 30, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Sangillo|first=Gregg|title=Texas, 36th House District|url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/congress-legacy/texas-36th-house-district-20121101|access-date=13 February 2013|newspaper=National Journal|date=1 November 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130130174630/http://www.nationaljournal.com/congress-legacy/texas-36th-house-district-20121101|archive-date=January 30, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 1995, Stockman wrote an article for ''[[Guns & Ammo]]'' claiming that the [[Waco siege]] had been orchestrated by the Clinton administration in order \"to prove the need for a ban on so-called 'assault weapons.'\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Whatever Happened to the Class of 1994?: The right-wing firebrands who charged into Congress in 1994 launched the missile that impeached Bill Clinton. Now, more than a third of the renegades are out of office\u2014and those who remain are becoming Washington insiders. in out But it may have been a kamikaze mission|author=Dana Milbank|newspaper=New York Times|date=January 17, 1999|section=Sunday Magazine|page=36}}</ref> He wrote further that \"[h]ad Bill Clinton really been unhappy with what Attorney General [[Janet Reno]] ordered, he would not only have fired her, he would have had Reno indicted for premeditated murder.\" After the article was published, Stockman's office denied that he believed in Waco \"conspiracy theories.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Holmes|first=Steven A.|title=Terror in Oklahoma: In Congress; Congressman Calls Raid Near Waco A Clinton Plot|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/05/13/us/terror-in-oklahoma-in-congress-congressman-calls-raid-near-waco-a-clinton-plot.html|accessdate=February 1, 2014|newspaper=The New York Times|date=May 13, 1995}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Schmidt|first=Susan|title=Rep. Stockman Says Raid On Cult Had Political Aim|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=May 13, 1995|page=A08}}</ref>\n\nIn 1995, Stockman called for a Congressional investigation into [[Alfred Kinsey]]'s 1948 study ''[[Sexual Behavior in the Human Male]]'' after learning that Kinsey had used data from the diary of a pedophile.<ref>{{cite news|last=Fisher|first=Marc|title=Critics: Sex Ed A Sham Since Kinsey Used Pedophile's Data|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19951212&slug=2157358|accessdate=1 February 2014|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=12 December 1995}}</ref> Stockman believed that the allegations discredited current theories of [[sexual education]] in the United States, writing to his congressional colleagues that\"[o]ur children have been taught that ... any type of sex is a valid outlet for their emotions. They are taught that the problem with sex is not that it is wrong to engage in homosexual, bestial, underage, or premarital sex, but that it is wrong to do so without protection.\"<ref name=\"Swartz\"/>\n\nIn 1995 and 1996, Stockman was proud to have played a role in the federal government's shutdown.<ref name=Clueless>[https://www.texasmonthly.com/politics/congressman-clueless/ Congressman Clueless], ''[[Texas Monthly]]'', Mimi Swartz, February 1996. Retrieved October 16, 2018.</ref> A 2010 [[Congressional Research Service]] report summarized other details of the 1995\u20131996 government shutdowns, indicating the shutdown impacted all sectors of the economy. Health and welfare services for military veterans were curtailed; the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] stopped disease surveillance; new clinical research patients were not accepted at the [[National Institutes of Health]]; and toxic waste cleanup at 609 sites was halted. Other impacts included: the closure of 368 National Park sites resulted in the loss of some seven million visitors; 200,000 applications for passports were not processed; and 20,000-30,000 applications by foreigners for visas went unprocessed each day; U.S. tourism and airline industries incurred millions of dollars in losses; more than 20% of federal contracts, representing $3.7 billion in spending, were affected adversely. The first of the two shutdowns caused the furlough of about 800,000 workers, while the second caused about 284,000 workers to be furloughed. They were said to have cost Stockman his reelection in 1996, and the Republican loss of seven seats the House.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/politics/documents/RL34680.pdf|title=Shutdown of the Federal Government: Causes, Processes, and Effects|date=February 18, 2011|publisher=[[Congressional Research Service]] (via [[The Washington Post]])|author=Brass, Clinton T.|accessdate=October 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\n'''Committee assignments'''\n\n* [[United States House Committee on Financial Services|House Committee on Banking and Financial Services]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Griffith|first=Pat|title=Kaptur calls for date on Mexico bailout|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=wF1IAAAAIBAJ&sjid=YQMEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3735,2754040&dq=steve+stockman+committee&hl=en|accessdate=13 February 2013|newspaper=Toledo Blade|date=Feb 11, 1995|location=Washington|page=3}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Washington Digest|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=ST&s_site=dfw&p_multi=ST&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAF9031D30874DC&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|accessdate=13 February 2013|newspaper=Fort Worth Star-Telegram|date=November 8, 1995}}</ref>\n** [[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations|Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations]]\n* [[United States House Committee on Science, Space and Technology|House Committee on Science]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://congressmanstevestockman.com/meet-steve/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-02-11 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130117185029/http://congressmanstevestockman.com/meet-steve/ |archive-date=January 17, 2013 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n** [[United States House Science Subcommittee on Energy|Subcommittee on Energy]]\n** [[United States House Science Subcommittee on Environment|Subcommittee on Environment]]\n\n==Inter-congressional career (1997\u20132013)==\nIn 1998, Stockman ran unsuccessfully in the Republican primary for the [[Texas Railroad Commission]].<ref name=nr1/>\n\nBetween 2005 and 2007, Stockman worked with the conservative [[Leadership Institute]]<ref name=nr1/> as director of its [[Campus Leadership Program]].<ref>[http://www.nationaljournal.com/congress/texas-36th-house-district-20121101 Texas, 36th House District] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131217225128/http://www.nationaljournal.com/congress/texas-36th-house-district-20121101 |date=December 17, 2013 }} ''[[National Journal]]''. Retrieved December 17, 2013</ref>\n\nIn 2006, he attempted to run as an [[Independent (politics)|Independent]] candidate for [[Texas's 22nd congressional district]], [[Tom DeLay]]'s former seat, and even though he had enough signatures to qualify for ballot access, the Texas Secretary of State invalidated enough signatures to make him ineligible.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/politics/3994768.html |title=Stockman fails to get enough names \u2013 Houston Chronicle |publisher=Chron.com |date=2006-06-23 |accessdate=2013-01-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freerepublic.com/focus/f-news/1654153/posts |title=Texas Secretary Of State Rules Stockman Can't Run For Congress - Fort Bend Now |publisher=Fortbendnow.com |date=2006-06-22 |accessdate=2016-06-27}}</ref> Stockman registered for the special election to fill out the remainder of DeLay's term; he was one of five candidates.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.sos.state.tx.us/elections/forms/candidates/2006con.pdf | title=Races with Candidates with Addresses Report | publisher=Texas Secretary of State | access-date=2006-09-01 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060830201344/http://www.sos.state.tx.us/elections/forms/candidates/2006con.pdf | archive-date=August 30, 2006 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> He finished third, with 10.75% of the vote.\n\nDuring his time away from Congress, Stockman also cared for his father, who had [[Alzheimer's disease]]. The cost of caring for him drove Stockman to declare [[bankruptcy]]<ref>''In re Stephen E. Stockman and Patti F. Stockman'', case no. 02-33843-H3-7, U.S. Bankruptcy Court for the Southern District of Texas (Houston Div.); petition filed April 5, 2002; discharge granted Oct. 24, 2002; case closed Oct. 24, 2002.</ref> and, when his father's disease became too severe, Stockman moved him to a veteran's home. When his father died, Stockman decided to run for Congress in the 2012 elections.<ref name=nr1/>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives (2013\u20132015)==\n[[File:Steve Stockman (9924706946).jpg|thumb|Stockman at the 2013 [[Liberty Political Action Conference]]]]\n\n===Election===\nIn 2011 Stockman formed an [[exploratory committee]], Friends of Steve Stockman, to consider a run for the [[Texas's 14th congressional district|14th district]] seat being vacated by unsuccessful presidential candidate [[Ron Paul]]. Stockman instead ran in 2012 in the newly created 36th District.  It included the Harris County portion of Friendswood, where Stockman's home was located. The district was drawn to be heavily Republican, and it was understood that whoever won the Republican primary would be the district's first congressman. In the May 29 primary, Stockman finished second in the first round, behind Stephen Vincent Takach, a financial planner. Takach finished with 22 percent of the vote, far short of the 50 percent threshold required to win.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://enr.sos.state.tx.us/enr/results/may29_160_state.htm|title=Republican primary election returns, May 29, 2012|publisher=enr.sos.state.tx.us|access-date=May 30, 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20120610141810/http://enr.sos.state.tx.us/enr/results/may29_160_state.htm|archive-date=June 10, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Stockman defeated Takach in the July 31 runoff 55%\u201345%, all but assuring his return to Congress after a 16-year absence.<ref name=nyt>{{cite news|url=http://elections.nytimes.com/2012/primaries/congress/texas|title=Texas Congressional Primaries \u2013 Election Results|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 7, 2013|accessdate=August 2, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn the November [[general election]], Stockman defeated [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] Max Owen Martin, a retired pilot from [[Clear Lake City, Texas]], with 71% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://team1.sos.state.tx.us/enr/results/nov06_164_state.htm?x=0&y=8111&id=401|title=Texas general election returns, November 6, 2012|publisher=Texas Secretary of State|accessdate=November 10, 2012}}{{Dead link|date=June 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nIn 2013, Stockman was one of ten Republicans who did not vote for [[John Boehner]] (R-OH) for [[Speaker of the U.S. House of Representatives|Speaker of the House]]; he was the only representative to vote \"Present\" as his protest vote.<ref>{{cite news|last=Blake|first=Aaron|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-fix/wp/2013/01/03/who-voted-against-boehner-for-speaker-and-why/ |title=Who voted against Boehner for speaker and why? |newspaper=Washington Post |date=January 3, 2013 |accessdate=August 3, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Kasperowicz |first=Pete |url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/house/275419-boehner-re-elected-speaker-with-some-gop-defections#ixzz2HnwHNibn |title=Boehner reelected as Speaker; nine Republicans defect in vote \u2013 The Hill's Floor Action |publisher=Thehill.com |date=January 3, 2013 |accessdate=January 16, 2013}}</ref>\n\nStockman opposes the [[Affordable Care Act]] (ACA). In 2013, Stockman supported a [[United States federal government shutdown of 2013|government shutdown]] caused by Republican members of Congress who sought to block a [[continuing resolution]] that includes funding for the Affordable Care Act.<ref>Sabrina Siddiqui, [https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/08/08/steve-stockman-obamacare_n_3728156.html Steve Stockman: People In Wheelchairs Help Democrats Win Health Care Argument], ''Huffington Post'' (August 8, 2013).</ref> Stockman's last-minute decision to challenge Cornyn in the Republican primary for Senate was \"sparked in part by Cornyn's role in helping end\" the federal shutdown.<ref>Brian Rogers & Margaret Kadifa, [http://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/article/Former-Rep-Steve-Stockman-charged-with-diverting-11009129.php Former U.S. Rep. Steve Stockman blames 'deep state' conspiracy for arrest], ''Houston Chronicle'' (March 17, 2017).</ref>\n\nIn January 2013, Stockman introduced the \"Safe Schools Act,\" a bill that would repeal the [[Gun-Free School Zones Act of 1990]]. Stockman introduced the bill following the [[Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting]]. He asserted that \"By disarming qualified citizens and officials in schools we have created a dangerous situation for our children.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yourhoustonnews.com/bay_area/news/stockman-introduces-audit-the-fed-act-safe-schools-act-to/article_479e84a3-e51b-5360-80d8-34f47b23a242.html |title=Stockman introduces Audit The Fed Act, Safe Schools Act to repeal 'Gun Free School Zones' \u2013 Your Houston News: News |publisher=Your Houston News |date=2013-01-07 |accessdate=2013-01-16}}</ref> The same month, Stockman issued a press release condemning [[gun control]] [[executive order]]s issued by [[Barack Obama|President Barack Obama]] post-Sandy Hook, stating, \"I will seek to thwart this action by any means necessary, including but not limited to eliminating funding for implementation, defunding the White House, and even filing [[articles of impeachment]].\"<ref>{{cite press release |last=Stockman |first=Steve |title=Obama's gun grab an unconstitutional threat to the nation |date=January 14, 2013 |publisher=House.gov |location=Washington DC |url=http://stockman.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/stockman-warns-obama-push-for-gun-control-will-be-met-with-white-house |access-date=2013-01-18 |quote=The White House's recent announcement they will use executive orders and executive actions to infringe on our constitutionally-protected right to keep and bear arms is an unconstitutional and unconscionable attack on the very founding principles of this republic. I will seek to thwart this action by any means necessary, including but not limited to eliminating funding for implementation, defunding the White House, and even filing articles of impeachment. |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116164518/http://stockman.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/stockman-warns-obama-push-for-gun-control-will-be-met-with-white-house |archive-date=January 16, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2013, Stockman voted against the re-authorization of the [[Violence Against Women Act]], objecting to provisions in the bill that expanded protections for transgender victims of domestic violence. Stockman said, \"This is helping the liberals, this is horrible. Unbelievable. What really bothers\u2014it's called a women's act, but then they have men dressed up as women, they count that. Change-gender, or whatever. How is that\u2014how is that a woman?\"<ref name=nr1>{{cite magazine|last=Woodruff |first=Betsy |title=Back in the Saddle |date=March 18, 2013 |magazine=National Review |url=http://www.nationalreview.com/articles/342824/back-saddle-betsy-woodruff |accessdate=March 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn April 25, 2014, Stockman stated that the [[House Ethics Committee]] was investigating a campaign finance reporting error made by a former campaign worker. Stockman stated that the mistake was corrected soon after he learned of it, and that the worker had been removed from the campaign organization.<ref>Matthew Daly, \"Texas Rep. Stockman says ethics inquiry underway,\" April 26, 2014, Associated Press, at [https://news.yahoo.com/texas-rep-stockman-says-ethics-inquiry-underway-215614889.html].</ref>\n\n'''Committee assignments'''\n\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|Committee on Foreign Affairs]]'''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thevindicator.com/news/article_3dee5bbc-5b45-11e2-986f-0019bb2963f4.html |title=Stockman named to Science, Foreign Affairs committees \u2013 The Vindicator: News |newspaper=The Vindicator |date=2013-01-10 |accessdate=2013-01-16}}</ref>\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on Africa, Global Health, Global Human Rights and International Organizations|Subcommittee on Africa, Global Health, Global Human Rights and International Organizations]]\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on Europe, Eurasia and Emerging Threats|Subcommittee on Europe, Eurasia and Emerging Threats]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Science, Space and Technology|Committee on Science, Space and Technology]]'''\n** [[United States House Science Subcommittee on Research|Subcommittee on Research]]\n** [[United States House Science Subcommittee on Space|Subcommittee on Space]]\n\n'''Caucus memberships'''\n\n* [[Congressional Constitution Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://congressionalconstitutioncaucus-garrett.house.gov/about-us/membership|format=|publisher=Congressional Constitution Caucus|date=|accessdate=8 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==2014 U.S. Senate election==\n{{main|2014 United States Senate election in Texas#Republican primary}}\nOn December 9, 2013, Stockman filed for the Republican nomination for U.S. Senate for Texas against incumbent U.S. Senator [[John Cornyn]].<ref name=\"WoodruffNR12092013\">Woodruff, Betsy. [http://www.nationalreview.com/corner/365887/stockman-will-primary-cornyn-betsy-woodruff Stockman Will Primary Cornyn], ''[[National Review]]'', December 9, 2013.</ref><ref name=\"GlueckPolitico12092013\">{{cite web | last = Glueck | first = Katie | title = In surprise, Steve Stockman challenges John Cornyn | work = [[Politico]] | date = December 9, 2013 | url = http://www.politico.com/story/2013/12/steve-stockman-john-cornyn-texas-senate-primary-100924.html?hp=f3}}</ref> On December 31, Stockman visited [[Bitcoin Center NYC]] to raise money and became the first U.S. Senate candidate to officially accept campaign contributions in cryptocurrency.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/azeem-khan/heres-why-the-nyc-bitcoin_b_4551792.html |title=Why the NYC Bitcoin Center Matters|work=[[Huffington Post]]|author=Azeem Khan|date=January 7, 2014|accessdate=August 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDonald \"Donny\" Ferguson, the former executive director of [[American Tradition Partnership|Western Tradition Partnership/American Tradition Partnership]] (ATP) and manager of their Washington, D.C. office, resigned on 3 January 2013, as it continued to suffer adverse rulings in Montana courts over alleged campaign finance violations.<ref>[http://billingsgazette.com/news/state-and-regional/montana/director-of-shadowy-political-group-atp-resigns-group-faces-more/article_40305b71-fe68-572c-a52d-52ba983cf12e.html 'Director of shadowy political group ATP resigns; group faces more legal troubles'], [[Billings Gazette]], By Mike Dennison, 4 January 2013. Retrieved May 25, 2018.</ref> Ferguson then became the congressional staffer and then U.S. Senate campaign spokesperson for Stockman.<ref>[http://www.texastribune.org/2014/02/23/stockman-camp-denies-allegations-election-miscondu/ Stockman Campaign Denies It Was Behind Mailer], [[Texas Tribune]],\nAman Batheja, 23 February 2014. Retrieved 25 May 2018.</ref>\n\nOn March 4, 2014, Stockman polled 250,759 votes (19.2 percent) in his bid for the Republican nomination for the Senate.<ref>\"Cornyn easily wins GOP nomination for US Senate,\" Associated Press, March 4, 2014, from KHOU-TV Houston, at [https://archive.is/20140305030722/http://www.khou.com/news/election/US-Sen-Cornyn-wins-Republican-nomination-in-Texas-248474551.html].</ref> He placed second in a field of eight candidates on the ballot. Cornyn received 778,967 votes (59.44 percent).<ref name=\"enr.sos.state.tx.us\">{{cite web|url=https://team1.sos.state.tx.us/enr/results/mar04_169_state.htm?x=0&y=218&id=176|title=Republican primary election returns, March 4, 2014|publisher=enr.sos.state.tx.us|access-date=March 5, 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.is/20140305180619/https://team1.sos.state.tx.us/enr/results/mar04_169_state.htm?x=0&y=218&id=176|archive-date=March 5, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Texas 2014 Primary Results|url=http://elections.nytimes.com/2014/results/primaries/texas|accessdate=6 March 2014|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref>  On election night, Stockman quickly conceded and called upon Texas Republicans to vote the straight party ticket on November 4, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hotair.com/archives/2014/03/04/cornyn-crushes-stockman-in-texas-primary/|title=Mary Katherine Ham, \"Cornyn crushes Stockman in Texas primary\", March 4, 2014|publisher=hotair.com|accessdate=March 6, 2014|date=2014-03-05}}</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, [[Brian Babin]] won the seat for District 36 as Stockman did not contest this seat.\n\n==Criminal case==\nIn March 2017, Stockman was arrested for allegedly conspiring to use contributions designated for a charity to fund his campaign and for personal use, a felony, under {{usc|18|371}}.\n\nAccording to the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] (FBI), in January 2013, Stockman requested and received $350,000 in donations from an unidentified businessman. Stockman allegedly solicited the money by using the name of Life Without Limits, a Las Vegas-based nonprofit intended to help people who have experienced traumatic events. The donation was allegedly intended to be used to renovate the Freedom House in Washington D.C.<ref name=\"chronart\">{{cite news|last1=Hunt|first1=Dianna|last2=Kadifa|first2=Margaret|title=Former Rep. Steve Stockman charged with diverting charitable funds to campaign|url=http://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/article/Former-Rep-Steve-Stockman-charged-with-diverting-11009129.php|accessdate=17 March 2017|agency=Chron|publisher=[[Hearst Newspapers, LLC]]|date=17 March 2017|ref=1}}</ref>\n\nStockman was also charged with conspiracy to falsify statements when reporting contributions to try to launder the money.<ref name=\"houstonart\">{{cite news|last1=Flynn|first1=Maegan|title=Tea Partier Steve Stockman Accused of Using Charity Cash For Campaign|url=http://www.houstonpress.com/news/steve-stockman-accused-of-violating-election-law-9282053|accessdate=17 March 2017|agency=Houston Press, LP|date=17 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.click2houston.com/news/former-texas-congressman-steve-stockman-accused-of-violating-federal-election-law |title=Former Texas Congressman Steve Stockman accused of violating federal election law|location=Houston, TX |publisher=KPRC |date=16 March 2017 |accessdate=17 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe FBI alleged that at the time of the events in question, Stockman had no formal control of the Life Without Limits organization, but that he had opened multiple bank accounts under the name \"Stephen E Stockman dba Life Without Limits.\" The FBI also alleged that financial records indicate that Stockman \"made no significant expenditures toward the purchase, renovation, or operation of the 'Freedom House,' which was never opened.\"<ref>Criminal Complaint and Affidavit, ''United States v. Stephen E. Stockman'', case no. 17-mj-00331, U.S. District Court for the Southern District of Texas.</ref>\n\nStockman conspired with Thomas Dodd, a former campaign worker and congressional special assistant. According to the ''Houston Chronicle'', the alleged conspiracy involved attempts \"to bilk conservative foundations out of at least $775,000 in donations meant for charitable purposes or voter education\". Dodd was indicted by a Federal grand jury in Houston and, on March 20, 2017, he pleaded guilty.<ref>Lise Olsen, \"Alleged scam by Stockman detailed,\" March 23, 2017, pages A1 and A13, ''Houston Chronicle''.</ref><ref>''United States v. Thomas Dodd'', case no. 17-cr-00116, U.S. District Court for the Southern District of Texas.</ref> Dodd was sentenced to 18 months and ordered to pay a fine of $800,000.<ref name=Posey/>\n\nStockman staffer Jason Posey entered a guilty plea before Chief U.S. District Judge [[Lee Rosenthal]] to counts of wire fraud, mail fraud, and money laundering. He faced a prison term of up to 45 years and a fine of more than $4.8 million, plus hundreds of thousands more in restitution. Posey admitted that at Stockman's direction he and Dodd illegally funneled hundreds of thousands of dollars from charitable foundations and individuals in charge of the foundations to pay for Stockman's campaigns and personal expenses. On April 2, 2019, Posey was sentenced to 18 months and ordered to pay a fine of $720,000.<ref name=Posey>[https://www.clarionledger.com/story/news/local/2019/04/02/tupelo-man-sentenced-wire-fraud-case-connected-gop-lawmaker/3345335002/ Tupelo man sentenced in wire fraud case connected to GOP lawmaker], ''[[Associated Press]]'', April 2, 2019. Retrieved April 9, 2019.</ref>\n\nOn March 28, 2017, a federal grand jury issued a 28 count indictment that included 24 counts against Stockman. He was accused of obtaining $1.25 million under false pretenses and using the funds for his political campaigns.<ref>Josh Gerstein, \"Ex-congressman Stockman indicted in Texas,\" March 28, 2017, politico.com, at [http://www.politico.com/story/2017/03/steve-stockman-texas-indicted-236616].</ref> He was charged with eleven counts of money laundering, eight counts of mail and wire fraud, one count of conspiracy to make \"conduit contributions\" and false statements (conspiracy to conceal the real source of the contributions by false attribution), two counts of making false statements to the [[Federal Election Commission]], one count of making excessive contributions, and one count of willfully filing a false 2013 Federal income tax return by not reporting some of his income. Posey was charged with money laundering, mail and wire fraud, conspiracy to make conduit contributions and false statements, making false statements to the Federal Election Commission,  making excessive contributions, and falsification of records.<ref>News Release, \"Former Texas Congressman and Associate Indicted on Conspiracy Charges,\" March 28, 2017, United States Department of Justice, at {{cite web |url=https://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/former-texas-congressman-and-associate-indicted-conspiracy-charges |title=Archived copy |access-date=2017-03-29 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170329141723/https://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/former-texas-congressman-and-associate-indicted-conspiracy-charges |archive-date=March 29, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}.</ref><ref>First Superseding Indictment, March 28, 2017, docket entry 23, ''United States v. Stephen E. Stockman, Jason T. Posey'', case no. 17-cr-00116, U.S. District Court for the Southern District of Texas (Houston Div.).</ref> Due to its complexity and the need for time to review 142,378 pages of documents [[Brady disclosure|disclosed]] by the prosecution, a motion for postponement of Stockman's trial by his court-appointed attorney was granted. His trial began on January 29, 2018.<ref>[http://www.courthousenews.com/former-texas-congressmans-fraud-trial-delayed-2018/ Former Texas Congressman\u2019s Fraud Trial Pushed to 2018], ''[[Courthouse News Service]]'', Cameron Langford, April 27, 2017. Retrieved July 24, 2017.</ref><ref>[http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/ex-hill-staffer-pleads-guilty-for-running-money-laundering-ring-on-behalf-of-former-rep-steve-stockman/article/2637235 Ex-Hill staffer pleads guilty for running money laundering ring on behalf of former rep Steve Stockman], ''[[Washington Examiner]]'', Kelly Cohen, Oct 11, 2017. Retrieved December 23, 2017.</ref>\n\nOn April 12, 2018, Stockman was convicted by a jury on 23 of the 24 felony counts against him, for which he faced up to 20 years in prison for each count. He was acquitted on one count of wire fraud. Because he was judged to be a flight risk, he was remanded into custody pending sentencing,<ref name=\"texasmonthly.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.texasmonthly.com/politics/jury-peers-karma-convict-steve-stockman/|title=A Jury of His Peers\u2014and Karma\u2014Convict Steve Stockman|date=12 April 2018|publisher=|accessdate=8 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2018/04/12/texas-congressman-steve-stockman-found-guilty-felony-charges/|title=Former Texas congressman Steve Stockman found guilty of 23 felonies|first=The Texas|last=Tribune|date=12 April 2018|publisher=|accessdate=8 November 2018}}</ref> which was re-set for November 7, 2018.\n\nOn November 7, 2018, he was sentenced to serve ten years in prison and ordered to pay $1,014,718.51 in restitution, to be followed by three years of supervised release.<ref name=\"sentence\">{{cite web|url=https://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/former-us-congressman-sentenced-10-years-prison-extensive-fraud-tax-and-election-crimes |title=Former U.S. Congressman Sentenced to 10 Years in Prison for Extensive Fraud, Tax, and Election Crimes Scheme |date=November 7, 2018 |accessdate=November 7, 2018 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Stockman is incarcerated at a facility of the [[Federal Bureau of Prisons]] at [[Beaumont, Texas]], and is scheduled for release on December 26, 2026.<ref>Stephen Ernest Stockman, inmate # 23502-479, [[Federal Bureau of Prisons]], U.S. Dep't of Justice, at [https://www.bop.gov/inmateloc/ Inmate locator].</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Michigan|Texas|Politics|Conservatism|Christianity}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Curlie|Regional/North_America/United_States/Texas/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Steve_Stockman_%5BR-36%5D|Steve Stockman}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=S000937 | votesmart=21703 | fec=H6TX22143 | congress=steve-stockman/1114 }}<!--\nLinks formerly displayed via the CongLinks template:\n* [http://ballotpedia.org/Steve_Stockman Biography] at [[Ballotpedia]]\n* [http://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/410396 Congressional profile] at [[GovTrack]]\n* [http://www.opencongress.org/people/show/410396 Congressional profile] at [[Participatory Politics Foundation|OpenCongress]]\n* [http://www.rollcall.com/members/1058.html Congressional profile] at ''[[Roll Call]]''\n* [http://www.politifact.com/personalities/steve-stockman Fact-checking] at [[PolitiFact.com]]\n* [http://www.opensecrets.org/politicians/summary.php?cid=N00005918 Financial information (federal office)] at [[Center for Responsive Politics|OpenSecrets.org]]\n* [http://www.followthemoney.org/database/uniquecandidate.phtml?uc=116575 Financial information (state office)] at the National Institute for Money in State Politics\n* [http://www.ontheissues.org/TX/Steve_Stockman.htm Issue positions and quotes] at [[On the Issues]]\n* [http://www.c-spanvideo.org/stevestockman02 Appearances] on [[C-SPAN]] programs\n* [https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2851b9da-4bbd-11e2-8758-b64a2997a921_topic.html Collected news and commentary] at ''[[The Washington Post]]''\n* -->\n*{{C-SPAN|Steve Stockman 02}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jack Brooks (American politician)|Jack Brooks]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Minnesota|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br/>from [[Texas's 9th congressional district]]|years=1995\u20131997}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Nick Lampson]]}}\n|-\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Minnesota|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br/>from [[Texas's 36th congressional district]]|years=2013\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Brian Babin]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{USCongRep-start|congresses= 104th & 113th [[United States Congress]] |state=[[Texas]]}}\n{{USCongRep/TX/104}}\n{{USCongRep/TX/113}}\n{{USCongRep-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stockman, Steve}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Baptists from Texas]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Texas]]\n[[Category:People from Bloomfield Hills, Michigan]]\n[[Category:People from Houston]]\n[[Category:Texas Republicans]]\n[[Category:University of Houston\u2013Clear Lake alumni]]\n[[Category:Republican Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Leadership Institute alumni and associates]]\n[[Category:People from Chambers County, Texas]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Texas politicians convicted of crimes]]\n[[Category:Baptists from Michigan]]\n[[Category:Texas Independents]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American politician from Texas}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Steve Stockman\n|image        = SteveStockmanCP.jpg\n|state        = [[Texas]]\n|district     = {{ushr|Texas|36|36th}}\n|term_start   = January 3, 2013\n|term_end     = January 3, 2015\n|predecessor  = ''Constituency established''\n|successor    = [[Brian Babin]]\n|state1       = [[Texas]]\n|district1    = {{ushr|Texas|9|9th}}\n|term_start1  = January 3, 1995\n|term_end1    = January 3, 1997\n|predecessor1 = [[Jack Brooks (American politician)|Jack Brooks]]\n|successor1   = [[Nick Lampson]]\n|birthname    = Stephen Ernest Stockman\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1956|11|14}}\n|birth_place  = [[Bloomfield Hills, Michigan|Bloomfield Hills]], [[Michigan]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n|death_date   =\n|death_place  =\n|nationality  = American\n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse       = Patti Ferguson (1988\u2013present)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.texasmarriagerecords.org/marriage-of-stephen-stockman-and-patti-ferguson.html|title=Stephen Stockman and Patti Ferguson, Married December 10, 1988|publisher=texasmarriagerecords.org|accessdate=August 2, 2012}}</ref>\n|alma_mater   = [[University of Houston\u2013Clear Lake|University of Houston, Clear Lake]]}}\n'''Stephen Ernest Stockman''' (born November 14, 1956) is an [[United States|American]] politician who is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] and a convicted felon. He served as the U.S. Representative for [[Texas's 9th congressional district]] from 1995 to 1997 and for [[Texas's 36th congressional district]] from 2013 to 2015. Stockman ran in the Republican primary for the [[United States Senate]] [[United States Senate election in Texas, 2014|in the 2014 election]] but lost  to incumbent Senator [[John Cornyn]].\n\n==Early life, education, and business career==\nStockman was born in [[Bloomfield Hills, Michigan|Bloomfield Hills]], [[Michigan]], outside [[Detroit]]. His parents were evangelistic Christian teachers.<ref name=Clueless/> He graduated from [[Dondero High School]] in [[Royal Oak, Michigan|Royal Oak]], Michigan. From 1985 to 1986, he attended [[San Jacinto College]] but dropped out because he suffered from what he called \"partying syndrome\". In 1977 as Stockman was reporting to jail for traffic tickets, the jailers found [[valium]] in his possession after his girlfriend allegedly hid some in his underwear. He was charged with felony possession of a controlled substance, but the charge was later dropped.<ref name=Swartz>{{cite journal|author=Mimi Swartz |title=Congressman Clueless |journal=Texas Monthly |date=February 1996 |url=http://www.texasmonthly.com/story/congressman-clueless/page/0/2}}</ref><ref name=Gillman>{{cite news|last=Gillman|first=Todd|title=In 1995, Stockman admitted jail time, felony charge. Today he denies that, accusing Cornyn allies of lying.|url=http://trailblazersblog.dallasnews.com/2014/01/in-1995-stockman-admitted-jail-time-felony-charge-today-he-denies-that-accusing-cornyn-allies-of-lying.html/|newspaper=Dallas Morning News|accessdate=1 February 2014}}</ref> He later became a [[Born again (Christianity)|born-again Christian]].<ref name=\"johngizzi\">John Gizzi, [http://www.humanevents.com/2012/07/07/steve-stockman-vies-for-36th-texas-district-seat/ Steve Stockman Vies for 36th Texas District Seat], ''[[Human Events]]'', July 7, 2012</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Christopher Hooks |title=Steve Stockman Can't Lose |date=December 20, 2013 |journal=Politico |url=http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2013/12/steve-stockman-john-cornyn-texas-senate-republican-primary-101412.html?hp=t1}}</ref> In 1990, he earned a bachelor's degree in [[accounting]] from the [[University of Houston\u2013Clear Lake]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Salesman, 33, to run for Brooks seat|newspaper=Houston Chronicle|date=December 20, 1989|page=26}}</ref>  He worked as a computer salesman in [[Friendswood, Texas]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Local candidates rush to replace outgoing incumbents|newspaper=Houston Chronicle|date=March 11, 1990|author=Alan Bernstein}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives (1995\u20131997)==\n===Elections===\n;1990\nStockman's first run for Congress was in March 1990 in [[Texas's 9th congressional district]].  The district, anchored by [[Beaumont, Texas|Beaumont]] and [[Galveston, Texas|Galveston]], had been represented by [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] [[Jack Brooks (American politician)|Representative Jack Brooks]] since 1953.  His primary challenger was Mayor Maury Meyers of [[Beaumont, Texas|Beaumont]].<ref name=brookswins>{{cite news|title=Primaries '90 \u2013 Rep. Brooks wins Dem contest; Meyers leads GOP opponent|newspaper=Houston Chronicle|date=March 15, 1990|author=Richard Stewart}}</ref> [[Oliver North]] made appearances at two of Stockman's fundraisers.<ref>{{cite news|title=Iran-contra figure North appears at Hance fund-raisers|newspaper=[[Dallas Morning News]]|date=February 3, 1990|author=Sam Attlesey|quote=In addition to the fee he received for appearing with Mr. Hance, Mr. North also will receive $25,000 for joining Republican congressional candidate Steve Stockman on Saturday in Beaumont and Houston.}}</ref>\n\nMeyers got 44.3% of the primary vote; Stockman, 41%.<ref name=brookswins/>  Since no candidate had a majority, there was a runoff election and, with the support of third-place finisher Steve Clifford,<ref name=loser>{{cite news|title=Loser backs Meyers in runoff|newspaper=Houston Chronicle|date=March 16, 1990|page=A25}}</ref> Meyers beat Stockman to win the Republican nomination.<ref>{{cite news|title=Shine gets GOP nod in race for Congress|newspaper=Austin American-Statesman|date=April 11, 1990|author1=Mike Ward|author2=Drew Parma|page=A9}}</ref>\n\n;1992\nStockman ran again in 1992 for the House in District 9. This time he was unopposed in the primary.<ref>{{cite news|title=Unopposed Republican candidates|newspaper=Houston Chronicle|date=March 1, 1992|page=15|section=Voter's Guide}}</ref>  The [[1992 Republican National Convention]] was held in Houston in August of that year. Stockman organized a \"congressional cruise\" on the [[Houston Ship Channel]] as a fundraising opportunity, but no members of Congress attended.<ref>{{cite news|title=National convention continues to have ripple effect locally|newspaper=Houston Chronicle|date=August 23, 1992|author=Alan Bernstein|page=C2}}</ref> Democrat Brooks defeated him 56% to 44%.<ref>{{cite news|title=House of Representatives [Part 2 of 2]|newspaper=Sacramento Bee|date=November 5, 1992|page=A16}}</ref>\n\n;1994\nStockman ran again for House District 9 in 1994. He had two challengers in the Republican primary: John LeCour and James Milburn.  Stockman finished the primary with a [[Landslide victory|landslide]] 74%.<ref>{{cite news|title=Election '94/Bentsen, Clark in runoff/District 25 victor to face Fontenot|newspaper=Houston Chronicle|date=March 9, 1994|author=Susan Warren}}</ref>\n\nHis Democratic opponent in the general election was, as before, incumbent Jack Brooks.  Initially the [[National Rifle Association]] (NRA) endorsed Brooks and even donated $5,000 to his cause, while the [[Gun Owners of America]] endorsed Stockman.<ref name=tenure>{{cite news|title=Rep. Brooks' long tenure in danger \u2013 The crime bill, his incumbency may sink the Democrat's bid for a 22nd term|newspaper=Austin American-Statesman|date=October 22, 1994|page=A13}}</ref>  However, a number of NRA members threatened to resign from the organization over the issue and the NRA withdrew their support for Brooks, remaining neutral in the race.<ref name=tenure/>  In a major upset, Stockman beat Brooks, who, had he won, would have become [[Dean of the United States House of Representatives]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Texan in line as House dean \u2013 Jack Brooks has reputation as in-your-face politician|newspaper=Fort Worth Star-Telegram|date=July 25, 1994|author=Ron Hutcheson|page=1}}</ref> by 51% to 49%.<ref>{{cite news|title=State Results|newspaper=Austin American-Statesman|date=November 9, 1994|page=A8}}</ref>\n\n;1996\nStockman ran unopposed in the 1996 Republican primary.<ref>{{cite news|title=Unopposed Republicans|newspaper=Houston Chronicle|date=March 3, 1996|page=16|section=Voter's Guide}}</ref>  In July a federal court ordered the boundaries of 13 Texas House districts to be redrawn because of racial [[gerrymandering]], although Stockman's district was barely affected.<ref>{{cite news|title=The shape of things to come/Judges shift district lines/New races ordered this year for seats in Houston, Dallas|newspaper=Houston Chronicle|date=August 7, 1996|author=Alan Bernstein|quote=9th District:Few changes made; first-term conservative still running in a majority Democratic and Anglo district stretching from Galveston to Beaumont.}}</ref>  Stockman won a [[Plurality (voting)|plurality]] in the November election with 46%, forcing a runoff against Democratic [[Jefferson County, Texas|Jefferson County]] assessor [[Nick Lampson]] in the runoff election.<ref>{{cite news|title=ELECTION '96/Stockman-Lampson runoff brawl may take place on national stage|newspaper=Houston Chronicle|date=November 7, 1996|page=34|author=Richard Stewart}}</ref>  Lampson won the runoff election with 53% of the vote<ref>{{cite news|title=Lampson, Brady, Bentsen win House seats in runoff election|newspaper=Austin American-Statesman|date=December 11, 1996|author=Michael Graczyk|page=A10}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nDuring his 1995 term, Stockman opposed the [[1994 economic crisis in Mexico|U.S. bailout of the Mexican peso]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Sangillo|first=Gregg|title=Texas, 36th House District|url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/congress-legacy/texas-36th-house-district-20121101|access-date=February 13, 2013|newspaper=National Journal|date=November 1, 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130130174630/http://www.nationaljournal.com/congress-legacy/texas-36th-house-district-20121101|archive-date=January 30, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Sangillo|first=Gregg|title=Texas, 36th House District|url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/congress-legacy/texas-36th-house-district-20121101|access-date=13 February 2013|newspaper=National Journal|date=1 November 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130130174630/http://www.nationaljournal.com/congress-legacy/texas-36th-house-district-20121101|archive-date=January 30, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 1995, Stockman wrote an article for ''[[Guns & Ammo]]'' claiming that the [[Waco siege]] had been orchestrated by the Clinton administration in order \"to prove the need for a ban on so-called 'assault weapons.'\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Whatever Happened to the Class of 1994?: The right-wing firebrands who charged into Congress in 1994 launched the missile that impeached Bill Clinton. Now, more than a third of the renegades are out of office\u2014and those who remain are becoming Washington insiders. in out But it may have been a kamikaze mission|author=Dana Milbank|newspaper=New York Times|date=January 17, 1999|section=Sunday Magazine|page=36}}</ref> He wrote further that \"[h]ad Bill Clinton really been unhappy with what Attorney General [[Janet Reno]] ordered, he would not only have fired her, he would have had Reno indicted for premeditated murder.\" After the article was published, Stockman's office denied that he believed in Waco \"conspiracy theories.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Holmes|first=Steven A.|title=Terror in Oklahoma: In Congress; Congressman Calls Raid Near Waco A Clinton Plot|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/05/13/us/terror-in-oklahoma-in-congress-congressman-calls-raid-near-waco-a-clinton-plot.html|accessdate=February 1, 2014|newspaper=The New York Times|date=May 13, 1995}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Schmidt|first=Susan|title=Rep. Stockman Says Raid On Cult Had Political Aim|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=May 13, 1995|page=A08}}</ref>\n\nIn 1995, Stockman called for a Congressional investigation into [[Alfred Kinsey]]'s 1948 study ''[[Sexual Behavior in the Human Male]]'' after learning that Kinsey had used data from the diary of a pedophile.<ref>{{cite news|last=Fisher|first=Marc|title=Critics: Sex Ed A Sham Since Kinsey Used Pedophile's Data|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19951212&slug=2157358|accessdate=1 February 2014|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=12 December 1995}}</ref> Stockman believed that the allegations discredited current theories of [[sexual education]] in the United States, writing to his congressional colleagues that\"[o]ur children have been taught that ... any type of sex is a valid outlet for their emotions. They are taught that the problem with sex is not that it is wrong to engage in homosexual, bestial, underage, or premarital sex, but that it is wrong to do so without protection.\"<ref name=\"Swartz\"/>\n\nIn 1995 and 1996, Stockman was proud to have played a role in the federal government's shutdown.<ref name=Clueless>[https://www.texasmonthly.com/politics/congressman-clueless/ Congressman Clueless], ''[[Texas Monthly]]'', Mimi Swartz, February 1996. Retrieved October 16, 2018.</ref> A 2010 [[Congressional Research Service]] report summarized other details of the 1995\u20131996 government shutdowns, indicating the shutdown impacted all sectors of the economy. Health and welfare services for military veterans were curtailed; the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] stopped disease surveillance; new clinical research patients were not accepted at the [[National Institutes of Health]]; and toxic waste cleanup at 609 sites was halted. Other impacts included: the closure of 368 National Park sites resulted in the loss of some seven million visitors; 200,000 applications for passports were not processed; and 20,000-30,000 applications by foreigners for visas went unprocessed each day; U.S. tourism and airline industries incurred millions of dollars in losses; more than 20% of federal contracts, representing $3.7 billion in spending, were affected adversely. The first of the two shutdowns caused the furlough of about 800,000 workers, while the second caused about 284,000 workers to be furloughed. They were said to have cost Stockman his reelection in 1996, and the Republican loss of seven seats the House.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/politics/documents/RL34680.pdf|title=Shutdown of the Federal Government: Causes, Processes, and Effects|date=February 18, 2011|publisher=[[Congressional Research Service]] (via [[The Washington Post]])|author=Brass, Clinton T.|accessdate=October 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\n'''Committee assignments'''\n\n* [[United States House Committee on Financial Services|House Committee on Banking and Financial Services]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Griffith|first=Pat|title=Kaptur calls for date on Mexico bailout|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=wF1IAAAAIBAJ&sjid=YQMEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3735,2754040&dq=steve+stockman+committee&hl=en|accessdate=13 February 2013|newspaper=Toledo Blade|date=Feb 11, 1995|location=Washington|page=3}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Washington Digest|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=ST&s_site=dfw&p_multi=ST&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAF9031D30874DC&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|accessdate=13 February 2013|newspaper=Fort Worth Star-Telegram|date=November 8, 1995}}</ref>\n** [[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations|Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations]]\n* [[United States House Committee on Science, Space and Technology|House Committee on Science]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://congressmanstevestockman.com/meet-steve/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-02-11 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130117185029/http://congressmanstevestockman.com/meet-steve/ |archive-date=January 17, 2013 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n** [[United States House Science Subcommittee on Energy|Subcommittee on Energy]]\n** [[United States House Science Subcommittee on Environment|Subcommittee on Environment]]\n\n==Inter-congressional career (1997\u20132013)==\nIn 1998, Stockman ran unsuccessfully in the Republican primary for the [[Texas Railroad Commission]].<ref name=nr1/>\n\nBetween 2005 and 2007, Stockman worked with the conservative [[Leadership Institute]]<ref name=nr1/> as director of its [[Campus Leadership Program]].<ref>[http://www.nationaljournal.com/congress/texas-36th-house-district-20121101 Texas, 36th House District] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131217225128/http://www.nationaljournal.com/congress/texas-36th-house-district-20121101 |date=December 17, 2013 }} ''[[National Journal]]''. Retrieved December 17, 2013</ref>\n\nIn 2006, he attempted to run as an [[Independent (politics)|Independent]] candidate for [[Texas's 22nd congressional district]], [[Tom DeLay]]'s former seat, and even though he had enough signatures to qualify for ballot access, the Texas Secretary of State invalidated enough signatures to make him ineligible.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/politics/3994768.html |title=Stockman fails to get enough names \u2013 Houston Chronicle |publisher=Chron.com |date=2006-06-23 |accessdate=2013-01-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freerepublic.com/focus/f-news/1654153/posts |title=Texas Secretary Of State Rules Stockman Can't Run For Congress - Fort Bend Now |publisher=Fortbendnow.com |date=2006-06-22 |accessdate=2016-06-27}}</ref> Stockman registered for the special election to fill out the remainder of DeLay's term; he was one of five candidates.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.sos.state.tx.us/elections/forms/candidates/2006con.pdf | title=Races with Candidates with Addresses Report | publisher=Texas Secretary of State | access-date=2006-09-01 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060830201344/http://www.sos.state.tx.us/elections/forms/candidates/2006con.pdf | archive-date=August 30, 2006 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> He finished third, with 10.75% of the vote.\n\nDuring his time away from Congress, Stockman also cared for his father, who had [[Alzheimer's disease]]. The cost of caring for him drove Stockman to declare [[bankruptcy]]<ref>''In re Stephen E. Stockman and Patti F. Stockman'', case no. 02-33843-H3-7, U.S. Bankruptcy Court for the Southern District of Texas (Houston Div.); petition filed April 5, 2002; discharge granted Oct. 24, 2002; case closed Oct. 24, 2002.</ref> and, when his father's disease became too severe, Stockman moved him to a veteran's home. When his father died, Stockman decided to run for Congress in the 2012 elections.<ref name=nr1/>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives (2013\u20132015)==\n[[File:Steve Stockman (9924706946).jpg|thumb|Stockman at the 2013 [[Liberty Political Action Conference]]]]\n\n===Election===\nIn 2011 Stockman formed an [[exploratory committee]], Friends of Steve Stockman, to consider a run for the [[Texas's 14th congressional district|14th district]] seat being vacated by unsuccessful presidential candidate [[Ron Paul]]. Stockman instead ran in 2012 in the newly created 36th District.  It included the Harris County portion of Friendswood, where Stockman's home was located. The district was drawn to be heavily Republican, and it was understood that whoever won the Republican primary would be the district's first congressman. In the May 29 primary, Stockman finished second in the first round, behind Stephen Vincent Takach, a financial planner. Takach finished with 22 percent of the vote, far short of the 50 percent threshold required to win.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://enr.sos.state.tx.us/enr/results/may29_160_state.htm|title=Republican primary election returns, May 29, 2012|publisher=enr.sos.state.tx.us|access-date=May 30, 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20120610141810/http://enr.sos.state.tx.us/enr/results/may29_160_state.htm|archive-date=June 10, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Stockman defeated Takach in the July 31 runoff 55%\u201345%, all but assuring his return to Congress after a 16-year absence.<ref name=nyt>{{cite news|url=http://elections.nytimes.com/2012/primaries/congress/texas|title=Texas Congressional Primaries \u2013 Election Results|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 7, 2013|accessdate=August 2, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn the November [[general election]], Stockman defeated [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] Max Owen Martin, a retired pilot from [[Clear Lake City, Texas]], with 71% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://team1.sos.state.tx.us/enr/results/nov06_164_state.htm?x=0&y=8111&id=401|title=Texas general election returns, November 6, 2012|publisher=Texas Secretary of State|accessdate=November 10, 2012}}{{Dead link|date=June 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nIn 2013, Stockman was one of ten Republicans who did not vote for [[John Boehner]] (R-OH) for [[Speaker of the U.S. House of Representatives|Speaker of the House]]; he was the only representative to vote \"Present\" as his protest vote.<ref>{{cite news|last=Blake|first=Aaron|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-fix/wp/2013/01/03/who-voted-against-boehner-for-speaker-and-why/ |title=Who voted against Boehner for speaker and why? |newspaper=Washington Post |date=January 3, 2013 |accessdate=August 3, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Kasperowicz |first=Pete |url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/house/275419-boehner-re-elected-speaker-with-some-gop-defections#ixzz2HnwHNibn |title=Boehner reelected as Speaker; nine Republicans defect in vote \u2013 The Hill's Floor Action |publisher=Thehill.com |date=January 3, 2013 |accessdate=January 16, 2013}}</ref>\n\nStockman opposes the [[Affordable Care Act]] (ACA). In 2013, Stockman supported a [[United States federal government shutdown of 2013|government shutdown]] caused by Republican members of Congress who sought to block a [[continuing resolution]] that includes funding for the Affordable Care Act.<ref>Sabrina Siddiqui, [https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/08/08/steve-stockman-obamacare_n_3728156.html Steve Stockman: People In Wheelchairs Help Democrats Win Health Care Argument], ''Huffington Post'' (August 8, 2013).</ref> Stockman's last-minute decision to challenge Cornyn in the Republican primary for Senate was \"sparked in part by Cornyn's role in helping end\" the federal shutdown.<ref>Brian Rogers & Margaret Kadifa, [http://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/article/Former-Rep-Steve-Stockman-charged-with-diverting-11009129.php Former U.S. Rep. Steve Stockman blames 'deep state' conspiracy for arrest], ''Houston Chronicle'' (March 17, 2017).</ref>\n\nIn January 2013, Stockman introduced the \"Safe Schools Act,\" a bill that would repeal the [[Gun-Free School Zones Act of 1990]]. Stockman introduced the bill following the [[Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting]]. He asserted that \"By disarming qualified citizens and officials in schools we have created a dangerous situation for our children.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yourhoustonnews.com/bay_area/news/stockman-introduces-audit-the-fed-act-safe-schools-act-to/article_479e84a3-e51b-5360-80d8-34f47b23a242.html |title=Stockman introduces Audit The Fed Act, Safe Schools Act to repeal 'Gun Free School Zones' \u2013 Your Houston News: News |publisher=Your Houston News |date=2013-01-07 |accessdate=2013-01-16}}</ref> The same month, Stockman issued a press release condemning [[gun control]] [[executive order]]s issued by [[Barack Obama|President Barack Obama]] post-Sandy Hook, stating, \"I will seek to thwart this action by any means necessary, including but not limited to eliminating funding for implementation, defunding the White House, and even filing [[articles of impeachment]].\"<ref>{{cite press release |last=Stockman |first=Steve |title=Obama's gun grab an unconstitutional threat to the nation |date=January 14, 2013 |publisher=House.gov |location=Washington DC |url=http://stockman.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/stockman-warns-obama-push-for-gun-control-will-be-met-with-white-house |access-date=2013-01-18 |quote=The White House's recent announcement they will use executive orders and executive actions to infringe on our constitutionally-protected right to keep and bear arms is an unconstitutional and unconscionable attack on the very founding principles of this republic. I will seek to thwart this action by any means necessary, including but not limited to eliminating funding for implementation, defunding the White House, and even filing articles of impeachment. |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116164518/http://stockman.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/stockman-warns-obama-push-for-gun-control-will-be-met-with-white-house |archive-date=January 16, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2013, Stockman voted against the re-authorization of the [[Violence Against Women Act]], objecting to provisions in the bill that expanded protections for transgender victims of domestic violence. Stockman said, \"This is helping the liberals, this is horrible. Unbelievable. What really bothers\u2014it's called a women's act, but then they have men dressed up as women, they count that. Change-gender, or whatever. How is that\u2014how is that a woman?\"<ref name=nr1>{{cite magazine|last=Woodruff |first=Betsy |title=Back in the Saddle |date=March 18, 2013 |magazine=National Review |url=http://www.nationalreview.com/articles/342824/back-saddle-betsy-woodruff |accessdate=March 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn April 25, 2014, Stockman stated that the [[House Ethics Committee]] was investigating a campaign finance reporting error made by a former campaign worker. Stockman stated that the mistake was corrected soon after he learned of it, and that the worker had been removed from the campaign organization.<ref>Matthew Daly, \"Texas Rep. Stockman says ethics inquiry underway,\" April 26, 2014, Associated Press, at [https://news.yahoo.com/texas-rep-stockman-says-ethics-inquiry-underway-215614889.html].</ref>\n\n'''Committee assignments'''\n\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|Committee on Foreign Affairs]]'''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thevindicator.com/news/article_3dee5bbc-5b45-11e2-986f-0019bb2963f4.html |title=Stockman named to Science, Foreign Affairs committees \u2013 The Vindicator: News |newspaper=The Vindicator |date=2013-01-10 |accessdate=2013-01-16}}</ref>\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on Africa, Global Health, Global Human Rights and International Organizations|Subcommittee on Africa, Global Health, Global Human Rights and International Organizations]]\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on Europe, Eurasia and Emerging Threats|Subcommittee on Europe, Eurasia and Emerging Threats]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Science, Space and Technology|Committee on Science, Space and Technology]]'''\n** [[United States House Science Subcommittee on Research|Subcommittee on Research]]\n** [[United States House Science Subcommittee on Space|Subcommittee on Space]]\n\n'''Caucus memberships'''\n\n* [[Congressional Constitution Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://congressionalconstitutioncaucus-garrett.house.gov/about-us/membership|format=|publisher=Congressional Constitution Caucus|date=|accessdate=8 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==2014 U.S. Senate election==\n{{main|2014 United States Senate election in Texas#Republican primary}}\nOn December 9, 2013, Stockman filed for the Republican nomination for U.S. Senate for Texas against incumbent U.S. Senator [[John Cornyn]].<ref name=\"WoodruffNR12092013\">Woodruff, Betsy. [http://www.nationalreview.com/corner/365887/stockman-will-primary-cornyn-betsy-woodruff Stockman Will Primary Cornyn], ''[[National Review]]'', December 9, 2013.</ref><ref name=\"GlueckPolitico12092013\">{{cite web | last = Glueck | first = Katie | title = In surprise, Steve Stockman challenges John Cornyn | work = [[Politico]] | date = December 9, 2013 | url = http://www.politico.com/story/2013/12/steve-stockman-john-cornyn-texas-senate-primary-100924.html?hp=f3}}</ref> On December 31, Stockman visited [[Bitcoin Center NYC]] to raise money and became the first U.S. Senate candidate to officially accept campaign contributions in cryptocurrency.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/azeem-khan/heres-why-the-nyc-bitcoin_b_4551792.html |title=Why the NYC Bitcoin Center Matters|work=[[Huffington Post]]|author=Azeem Khan|date=January 7, 2014|accessdate=August 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDonald \"Donny\" Ferguson, the former executive director of [[American Tradition Partnership|Western Tradition Partnership/American Tradition Partnership]] (ATP) and manager of their Washington, D.C. office, resigned on 3 January 2013, as it continued to suffer adverse rulings in Montana courts over alleged campaign finance violations.<ref>[http://billingsgazette.com/news/state-and-regional/montana/director-of-shadowy-political-group-atp-resigns-group-faces-more/article_40305b71-fe68-572c-a52d-52ba983cf12e.html 'Director of shadowy political group ATP resigns; group faces more legal troubles'], [[Billings Gazette]], By Mike Dennison, 4 January 2013. Retrieved May 25, 2018.</ref> Ferguson then became the congressional staffer and then U.S. Senate campaign spokesperson for Stockman.<ref>[http://www.texastribune.org/2014/02/23/stockman-camp-denies-allegations-election-miscondu/ Stockman Campaign Denies It Was Behind Mailer], [[Texas Tribune]],\nAman Batheja, 23 February 2014. Retrieved 25 May 2018.</ref>\n\nOn March 4, 2014, Stockman polled 250,759 votes (19.2 percent) in his bid for the Republican nomination for the Senate.<ref>\"Cornyn easily wins GOP nomination for US Senate,\" Associated Press, March 4, 2014, from KHOU-TV Houston, at [https://archive.is/20140305030722/http://www.khou.com/news/election/US-Sen-Cornyn-wins-Republican-nomination-in-Texas-248474551.html].</ref> He placed second in a field of eight candidates on the ballot. Cornyn received 778,967 votes (59.44 percent).<ref name=\"enr.sos.state.tx.us\">{{cite web|url=https://team1.sos.state.tx.us/enr/results/mar04_169_state.htm?x=0&y=218&id=176|title=Republican primary election returns, March 4, 2014|publisher=enr.sos.state.tx.us|access-date=March 5, 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.is/20140305180619/https://team1.sos.state.tx.us/enr/results/mar04_169_state.htm?x=0&y=218&id=176|archive-date=March 5, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Texas 2014 Primary Results|url=http://elections.nytimes.com/2014/results/primaries/texas|accessdate=6 March 2014|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref>  On election night, Stockman quickly conceded and called upon Texas Republicans to vote the straight party ticket on November 4, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hotair.com/archives/2014/03/04/cornyn-crushes-stockman-in-texas-primary/|title=Mary Katherine Ham, \"Cornyn crushes Stockman in Texas primary\", March 4, 2014|publisher=hotair.com|accessdate=March 6, 2014|date=2014-03-05}}</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, [[Brian Babin]] won the seat for District 36 as Stockman did not contest this seat.\n\n==Criminal case==\nIn March 2017, Stockman was arrested for allegedly conspiring to use contributions designated for a charity to fund his campaign and for personal use, a felony, under {{usc|18|371}}.\n\nAccording to the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] (FBI), in January 2013, Stockman requested and received $350,000 in donations from an unidentified businessman. Stockman allegedly solicited the money by using the name of Life Without Limits, a Las Vegas-based nonprofit intended to help people who have experienced traumatic events. The donation was allegedly intended to be used to renovate the Freedom House in Washington D.C.<ref name=\"chronart\">{{cite news|last1=Hunt|first1=Dianna|last2=Kadifa|first2=Margaret|title=Former Rep. Steve Stockman charged with diverting charitable funds to campaign|url=http://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/article/Former-Rep-Steve-Stockman-charged-with-diverting-11009129.php|accessdate=17 March 2017|agency=Chron|publisher=[[Hearst Newspapers, LLC]]|date=17 March 2017|ref=1}}</ref>\n\nStockman was also charged with conspiracy to falsify statements when reporting contributions to try to launder the money.<ref name=\"houstonart\">{{cite news|last1=Flynn|first1=Maegan|title=Tea Partier Steve Stockman Accused of Using Charity Cash For Campaign|url=http://www.houstonpress.com/news/steve-stockman-accused-of-violating-election-law-9282053|accessdate=17 March 2017|agency=Houston Press, LP|date=17 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.click2houston.com/news/former-texas-congressman-steve-stockman-accused-of-violating-federal-election-law |title=Former Texas Congressman Steve Stockman accused of violating federal election law|location=Houston, TX |publisher=KPRC |date=16 March 2017 |accessdate=17 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe FBI alleged that at the time of the events in question, Stockman had no formal control of the Life Without Limits organization, but that he had opened multiple bank accounts under the name \"Stephen E Stockman dba Life Without Limits.\" The FBI also alleged that financial records indicate that Stockman \"made no significant expenditures toward the purchase, renovation, or operation of the 'Freedom House,' which was never opened.\"<ref>Criminal Complaint and Affidavit, ''United States v. Stephen E. Stockman'', case no. 17-mj-00331, U.S. District Court for the Southern District of Texas.</ref>\n\nStockman conspired with Thomas Dodd, a former campaign worker and congressional special assistant. According to the ''Houston Chronicle'', the alleged conspiracy involved attempts \"to bilk conservative foundations out of at least $775,000 in donations meant for charitable purposes or voter education\". Dodd was indicted by a Federal grand jury in Houston and, on March 20, 2017, he pleaded guilty.<ref>Lise Olsen, \"Alleged scam by Stockman detailed,\" March 23, 2017, pages A1 and A13, ''Houston Chronicle''.</ref><ref>''United States v. Thomas Dodd'', case no. 17-cr-00116, U.S. District Court for the Southern District of Texas.</ref> Dodd was sentenced to 18 months and ordered to pay a fine of $800,000.<ref name=Posey/>\n\nStockman staffer Jason Posey entered a guilty plea before Chief U.S. District Judge [[Lee Rosenthal]] to counts of wire fraud, mail fraud, and money laundering. He faced a prison term of up to 45 years and a fine of more than $4.8 million, plus hundreds of thousands more in restitution. Posey admitted that at Stockman's direction he and Dodd illegally funneled hundreds of thousands of dollars from charitable foundations and individuals in charge of the foundations to pay for Stockman's campaigns and personal expenses. On April 2, 2019, Posey was sentenced to 18 months and ordered to pay a fine of $720,000.<ref name=Posey>[https://www.clarionledger.com/story/news/local/2019/04/02/tupelo-man-sentenced-wire-fraud-case-connected-gop-lawmaker/3345335002/ Tupelo man sentenced in wire fraud case connected to GOP lawmaker], ''[[Associated Press]]'', April 2, 2019. Retrieved April 9, 2019.</ref>\n\nOn March 28, 2017, a federal grand jury issued a 28 count indictment that included 24 counts against Stockman. He was accused of obtaining $1.25 million under false pretenses and using the funds for his political campaigns.<ref>Josh Gerstein, \"Ex-congressman Stockman indicted in Texas,\" March 28, 2017, politico.com, at [http://www.politico.com/story/2017/03/steve-stockman-texas-indicted-236616].</ref> He was charged with eleven counts of money laundering, eight counts of mail and wire fraud, one count of conspiracy to make \"conduit contributions\" and false statements (conspiracy to conceal the real source of the contributions by false attribution), two counts of making false statements to the [[Federal Election Commission]], one count of making excessive contributions, and one count of willfully filing a false 2013 Federal income tax return by not reporting some of his income. Posey was charged with money laundering, mail and wire fraud, conspiracy to make conduit contributions and false statements, making false statements to the Federal Election Commission,  making excessive contributions, and falsification of records.<ref>News Release, \"Former Texas Congressman and Associate Indicted on Conspiracy Charges,\" March 28, 2017, United States Department of Justice, at {{cite web |url=https://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/former-texas-congressman-and-associate-indicted-conspiracy-charges |title=Archived copy |access-date=2017-03-29 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170329141723/https://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/former-texas-congressman-and-associate-indicted-conspiracy-charges |archive-date=March 29, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}.</ref><ref>First Superseding Indictment, March 28, 2017, docket entry 23, ''United States v. Stephen E. Stockman, Jason T. Posey'', case no. 17-cr-00116, U.S. District Court for the Southern District of Texas (Houston Div.).</ref> Due to its complexity and the need for time to review 142,378 pages of documents [[Brady disclosure|disclosed]] by the prosecution, a motion for postponement of Stockman's trial by his court-appointed attorney was granted. His trial began on January 29, 2018.<ref>[http://www.courthousenews.com/former-texas-congressmans-fraud-trial-delayed-2018/ Former Texas Congressman\u2019s Fraud Trial Pushed to 2018], ''[[Courthouse News Service]]'', Cameron Langford, April 27, 2017. Retrieved July 24, 2017.</ref><ref>[http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/ex-hill-staffer-pleads-guilty-for-running-money-laundering-ring-on-behalf-of-former-rep-steve-stockman/article/2637235 Ex-Hill staffer pleads guilty for running money laundering ring on behalf of former rep Steve Stockman], ''[[Washington Examiner]]'', Kelly Cohen, Oct 11, 2017. Retrieved December 23, 2017.</ref>\n\nOn April 12, 2018, Stockman was convicted by a jury on 23 of the 24 felony counts against him, for which he faced up to 20 years in prison for each count. He was acquitted on one count of wire fraud. Because he was judged to be a flight risk, he was remanded into custody pending sentencing,<ref name=\"texasmonthly.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.texasmonthly.com/politics/jury-peers-karma-convict-steve-stockman/|title=A Jury of His Peers\u2014and Karma\u2014Convict Steve Stockman|date=12 April 2018|publisher=|accessdate=8 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2018/04/12/texas-congressman-steve-stockman-found-guilty-felony-charges/|title=Former Texas congressman Steve Stockman found guilty of 23 felonies|first=The Texas|last=Tribune|date=12 April 2018|publisher=|accessdate=8 November 2018}}</ref> which was re-set for November 7, 2018.\n\nOn November 7, 2018 he was sentenced to serve ten years in prison and ordered to pay $1,014,718.51 in restitution, to be followed by three years of supervised release.<ref name=\"sentence\">{{cite web|url=https://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/former-us-congressman-sentenced-10-years-prison-extensive-fraud-tax-and-election-crimes |title=Former U.S. Congressman Sentenced to 10 Years in Prison for Extensive Fraud, Tax, and Election Crimes Scheme |date=November 7, 2018 |accessdate=November 7, 2018 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Stockman is incarcerated at a facility of the [[Federal Bureau of Prisons]] at [[Beaumont, Texas]], and is scheduled for release on December 26, 2026.<ref>Stephen Ernest Stockman, inmate # 23502-479, [[Federal Bureau of Prisons]], U.S. Dep't of Justice, at [https://www.bop.gov/inmateloc/ Inmate locator].</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Michigan|Texas|Politics|Conservatism|Christianity}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Curlie|Regional/North_America/United_States/Texas/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Steve_Stockman_%5BR-36%5D|Steve Stockman}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=S000937 | votesmart=21703 | fec=H6TX22143 | congress=steve-stockman/1114 }}<!--\nLinks formerly displayed via the CongLinks template:\n* [http://ballotpedia.org/Steve_Stockman Biography] at [[Ballotpedia]]\n* [http://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/410396 Congressional profile] at [[GovTrack]]\n* [http://www.opencongress.org/people/show/410396 Congressional profile] at [[Participatory Politics Foundation|OpenCongress]]\n* [http://www.rollcall.com/members/1058.html Congressional profile] at ''[[Roll Call]]''\n* [http://www.politifact.com/personalities/steve-stockman Fact-checking] at [[PolitiFact.com]]\n* [http://www.opensecrets.org/politicians/summary.php?cid=N00005918 Financial information (federal office)] at [[Center for Responsive Politics|OpenSecrets.org]]\n* [http://www.followthemoney.org/database/uniquecandidate.phtml?uc=116575 Financial information (state office)] at the National Institute for Money in State Politics\n* [http://www.ontheissues.org/TX/Steve_Stockman.htm Issue positions and quotes] at [[On the Issues]]\n* [http://www.c-spanvideo.org/stevestockman02 Appearances] on [[C-SPAN]] programs\n* [https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2851b9da-4bbd-11e2-8758-b64a2997a921_topic.html Collected news and commentary] at ''[[The Washington Post]]''\n* -->\n*{{C-SPAN|Steve Stockman 02}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jack Brooks (American politician)|Jack Brooks]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Minnesota|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br/>from [[Texas's 9th congressional district]]|years=1995\u20131997}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Nick Lampson]]}}\n|-\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Minnesota|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br/>from [[Texas's 36th congressional district]]|years=2013\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Brian Babin]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{USCongRep-start|congresses= 104th & 113th [[United States Congress]] |state=[[Texas]]}}\n{{USCongRep/TX/104}}\n{{USCongRep/TX/113}}\n{{USCongRep-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stockman, Steve}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Baptists from Texas]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Texas]]\n[[Category:People from Bloomfield Hills, Michigan]]\n[[Category:People from Houston]]\n[[Category:Texas Republicans]]\n[[Category:University of Houston\u2013Clear Lake alumni]]\n[[Category:Republican Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Leadership Institute alumni and associates]]\n[[Category:People from Chambers County, Texas]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Texas politicians convicted of crimes]]\n[[Category:Baptists from 