033\u1004\u1039\u1015\u103c\u1032\u1010\u103c\u1004\u1039 \u1011\u103c\u1014\u1039\u1038\u1019\u1004\u1039\u1038\u108f\u103d\u1004\u1037\u1039 \u1011\u103c\u1014\u1039\u1038\u1011\u103c\u1014\u1039\u1038\u1031\u1021\u102c\u1004\u1039\u1010\u102f\u102d\u1037 \u1031\u101b\u108a\u1010\u1036 \u1006\u102d\u1015\u1039\u1006\u102f \u1006\u103c\u1010\u1039\u1001\u1030\u1038\u101b\u101b\u103d\u102d|website=myawady.net.mm}}</ref> \n*2012\tWBPF World Championships (4th Runner Up\u2014 Men Bodybuilding 60&nbsp;kg)\n*SEA Championships (1st Runner Up\u2014 Men Bodybuilding 60&nbsp;kg)\n*2011\tWBPF World Men's Bodybuilding Championships (3rd Runner Up\u2014 Men Bodybuilding 60&nbsp;kg)\n*Asian and World Bodybuilding & Physique Sports Championships (2nd Runner Up\u2014 Asian Men Bodybuilding 60&nbsp;kg)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tun Min}}\n[[Category:Burmese bodybuilders]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Professional bodybuilders]]\n[[Category:People from Magway Division]]\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Burmese male bodybuilders]]\n", "name_user": "Irrawaddy", "label": "safe", "comment": "Spelling/grammar/punctuation/typographical correction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tun_Min"}
{"title_page": "Kusunda language", "text_new": "{{Infobox language\n| name = Kusunda\n| altname = Ban Raja\n| nativename = ''mihaq''\n| states = [[Nepal]]\n| region = [[Gandaki Zone]]\n| ethnicity = 270 Kusunda (2011 census)\n| extinct = \n| ref = \n| familycolor = Isolate\n| family = [[Language isolate]]\n| iso3 = kgg\n| glotto = kusu1250\n| glottorefname = Kusunda\n| map = Kusunda_language.png\n| mapcaption = Ethnologue locations: (west) [[Dang Deukhuri District|Dang]] and [[Pyuthan District|Pyuthan]] districts (dark grey) within [[Rapti Zone]]; (center) [[Tanahu District]] within [[Gandaki Zone]]<br>EndangeredLanguages.com location: red<br>[[World Atlas of Language Structures|WALS]] location: purple ([[Gorkha District]])\n| notice = IPA\n}}\n\n'''Kusunda''' (Kusanda) is a [[language isolate]] spoken by a handful of people in western and central [[Nepal]]. It has only recently been described in any detail.\n\n==Rediscovery==\nFor decades the Kusunda language was thought to be on the verge of extinction, with little hope of ever knowing it well. The little material that could be gleaned from the memories of former speakers suggested that the language was an isolate, but without much evidence either way it was often classified along with its neighbors as [[Tibeto-Burman languages|Tibeto-Burman]]. However, in 2004 three [[Kusunda people|Kusunda]]s, Gyani Maya Sen, Prem Bahadur Shahi and Kamala Singh,<ref name=3Kusundas>{{cite web |url=http://listserv.emich.edu/cgi-bin/wa?A2=ind0410&L=endangered-languages-l&P=439 |title=Kusunda language does not fall in any family: Study |accessdate=2007-09-12 |last=Rana |first=B.K. |date=2004-10-12 |work=email with pasted news article |publisher=Himalayan News Service, Lalitpur, 2004-10-10 }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> were brought to [[Kathmandu]] for help with citizenship papers. There, members of [[Tribhuvan University]] discovered that one of them, a native of Sakhi VDC in southern [[Rolpa District]], was a fluent speaker of the language. Several of her relatives were also discovered to be fluent. There are now known to be at least seven or eight fluent speakers of the language, the youngest in her thirties.<ref name=\"Watters2006\"/> However, the language is [[moribund language|moribund]], with no children learning it, as all Kusunda speakers have married outside their ethnicity.<ref name=\"Watters2006\">Watters, David E. 2005. ''Kusunda: a typological isolate in South Asia.'' In Yogendra Yadava, Govinda Bhattarai, Ram Raj Lohani, Balaram Prasain and Krishna Parajuli (eds.), Contemporary issues in Nepalese linguistics p.&nbsp;375-396. Kathmandu: Linguistic Society of Nepal.</ref>\n\nIt was presumed that with the death of Rajamama Kusunda on 19 April 2018 the language went extinct, though Gyani Maiya Sen could be the only surviving speaker.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2018-04-19/rajamama-lone-kusunda-language-speaker-dies.html|title=Rajamama, lone Kusunda language speaker, dies|access-date=2018-06-18|language=en}}</ref>\n\nGyani Maiya Sen and her sister Kamala Kusunda who can speak the language fluently, together with author and researcher Uday Raj Aaley, have been teaching interested children and adults the Kusunda language. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2019/01/04/resuscitating-dying-kusunda-language|title=Resuscitating dying Kusunda language|last=|first=|date=4 January 2019|website=The Kathmandu Post|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nAaley, the facilitator and Kusunda language teacher, has authored the book \"Kusunda Tribe and Dictionary\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/art-entertainment/2017/08/01/book-that-traces-kusunda-tribes-history-hits-shelves|title=Book that traces Kusunda tribe's history hits shelves|last=|first=|date=1 August 2017|website=The Kathmandu Post|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref> The book has a compilation of over 1000 words from the Kusunda language. \n\n==Classification==\n[[David E. Watters|Watters]] (2005) published a mid-sized grammatical description of the language, plus vocabulary, which shows that Kusunda is indeed a language isolate, not just genealogically but also lexically, grammatically, and phonologically distinct from its neighbors. It appears that Kusunda is a remnant of the languages spoken in northern India before the influx of Tibeto-Burman- and [[Indo-Iranian languages|Indo-Iranian]]-speaking peoples, however it is not classified as a [[Munda languages|Munda]] or a [[Dravidian languages|Dravidian]] language. It thus joins [[Burushaski]], [[Nihali]] and (potentially) the substrate of the [[Vedda language]] in the list of South Asian languages which do not fall into the main categories of Indo-European, Dravidian, [[Sino-Tibetan languages|Sino-Tibetan]] and [[Austroasiatic languages|Austroasiatic]].\n\nBefore the recent discovery of active Kusunda speakers, there were several attempts to link the language to an established language family. B. K. Rana (2002) maintained that Kusunda is a [[Tibeto-Burman languages|Tibeto-Burman language]] as traditionally classified. Others have linked it to [[Munda languages|Munda]] (see [[David E. Watters|Watters]] 2005); [[Yeniseian languages|Yeniseian]] (Gurov 1989); [[Burushaski language|Burushaski]] and [[Caucasian languages|Caucasian]] (Reinhard and Toba 1970; this would be a variant of Gurov's proposal if [[Sino-Caucasian]] is accepted); the [[Nihali language|Nihali]] isolate in central India (Fleming 1996, Whitehouse 1997); and again with Nihali, as part of the [[Indo-Pacific languages|Indo-Pacific]] hypothesis (Whitehouse et al. 2004<ref>{{Cite journal\n| title = Kusunda: An Indo-Pacific language in Nepal\n| journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America\n| date = 2004-04-13\n| volume = 101\n| pages = 5692\u20135695                                     \n| url = http://www.pnas.org/content/101/15/5692.full\n|author1=Paul Whitehouse |author2=Timothy Usher | author3-link = Merritt Ruhlen\n|author3=Merritt Ruhlen |author4=William S.-Y. Wang | doi = 10.1073/pnas.0400233101\n| pmid = 15056764\n| issue = 15\n| pmc = 397480\n}}</ref>).\n\n[[John McWhorter]] supports [[Merritt Ruhlen]]'s argument of a relationship between Kusunda and the [[Oko-Juwoi language|Juwoi]] language spoken on the [[Andaman Islands]].<ref>John McWhorter, ''[[The Great Courses]]: Language Families of the World'', episode 14, \"Indian Languages That Aren't Indo-European\"</ref>\n\n==Phonology==\n\n===Vowels===\nPhonetically, Kusunda has six vowels in two [[vowel harmony|harmonic]] groups, which are arguably three vowels phonemically: a word will normally have vowels from the upper (pink) or lower (green) set, but not both simultaneously.  There are very few words that consistently have upper or lower vowels; most words may be pronounced either way, though those with [[uvular consonant]]s require the lower set (as in many languages). There are a few words with no uvular consonants that still bar such dual pronunciations, though these generally only feature the distinction in careful enunciation.<ref name=Watters/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|+Kusunda vowels\n! align=\"center\"| Vowels\n! align=\"center\"|[[Front vowel|Front]]\n! align=\"center\"|[[Central vowel|Central]]\n! align=\"center\"|[[Back vowel|Back]]\n|-\n|-\n|align=\"center\" |[[Close vowel|Close]]|| align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#ffcccc\" | {{IPA|i}} || || align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#ffcccc\"|{{IPA|u}}\n|-\n|align=\"center\" | [[Mid vowel|Mid]]|| align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#ccffcc\"| {{IPA|e}} || align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#ffcccc\"|{{IPA|\u0259}} || align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#ccffcc\"|{{IPA|o}}\n|-\n|align=\"center\" | [[Open vowel|Open]] || || align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#ccffcc\"| {{IPA|a}} || \n|}\n\n===Consonants===\nKusunda consonants seem to only contrast the active articulator, not where that articulator makes contact. For example, apical consonants may be [[dental consonant|dental]], [[alveolar consonant|alveolar]], [[retroflex consonant|retroflex]], or [[palatal consonant|palatal]]: {{IPA|/t/}} is dental {{IPA|[t\u032a]}} before {{IPA|/i/}}, alveolar {{IPA|[t\u0347]}} before {{IPA|/e, \u0259, u/}}, retroflex {{IPA|[\u0288]}} before {{IPA|/o, a/}}, and palatal {{IPA|[c]}} when there is a following uvular, as in {{IPA|[coq]}} ~ {{IPA|[t\u0347ok]}} ('we').<ref name=Watters/>\n\nIn addition, many consonants vary between [[stop consonant|stops]] and [[fricative consonant|fricative]]s; for instance, {{IPA|/p/}} seems to surface as {{IPA|[b]}} between vowels, while {{IPA|/b/}} surfaces as {{IPA|[\u03b2]}} in the same environment. [[Aspiration (phonetics)|Aspiration]] appears to be recent to the language. Kusunda also lacks the [[retroflex consonant]] phonemes common to the region, and is unique in the region in having [[uvular consonant]]s.<ref name=Watters/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+Consonants\n!\n! [[Labial consonant|Labial]]\n! [[Coronal consonant|Coronal]]\n! [[Palatal consonant|Palatal]]\n! [[Velar consonant|Velar]]\n! [[Uvular consonant|Uvular]]\n! [[Glottal consonant|Glottal]]\n|- \n| [[Nasal consonant|Nasal]]|| '''{{IPA|m}}''' || '''{{IPA|n}}''' || || '''{{IPA|\u014b}}''' || '''{{IPA|\u0274\u0295}}''' || \n|- \n| [[Plosive consonant|Plosive]]|| {{IPA|'''p~b<br>b~\u03b2'''<br>(p\u02b0 b\u02b1)}} || {{IPA|'''t~d<br>d'''<br>(t\u02b0 d\u02b1)}} || || {{IPA|'''k~\u0261<br>\u0261~\u0263'''<br>(k\u02b0~x \u0261\u02b1)}} || {{IPA|'''q~\u0262'''<br>(q\u02b0)}} || {{IPA|'''\u0294'''<br>&nbsp;}}\n|- \n| [[Affricate consonant|Affricate]]|| || {{IPA|'''ts<br>dz'''<br>(ts\u02b0 dz\u02b1)}} || || || || \n|- \n| [[Fricative consonant|Fricative]]|| || '''{{IPA|s}}''' || || || rowspan=2| '''{{IPA|\u0281~\u0295}}''' || rowspan=2| '''{{IPA|h}}'''\n|- \n| [[Approximant consonant|Approximant]]|| '''{{IPA|w}}''' || '''{{IPA|l}}''' || '''{{IPA|j}}''' || \n|- \n| [[Flap consonant|Flap]] || || '''{{IPA|\u027e}}''' || || || ||  \n|}\n\n{{IPA|[\u0295]}} does not occur initially, and {{IPA|[\u014b]}} only occurs at the end of a syllable, unlike in neighboring languages. {{IPA|[\u0274\u0295]}} only occurs between vowels; it may be |{{IPA|\u014b+\u0295}}|.<ref name=Watters/>\n\n==Pronouns==\n\nKusunda has several cases, marked on nouns and pronouns three of which are [[nominative]] (Kusunda, unlike its neighbors, has no [[ergativity]]), [[genitive]], and [[accusative case|accusative]] [[Grammatical person|persons]].<ref name=Watters>Watters (2005)</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Nominative\n! Singular\n! Plural\n|-\n|First person|| align=\"center\"| tsi || align=\"center\"| tok\n|-\n|Second person|| align=\"center\"| nu || align=\"center\"| nok\n|-\n|Third person|| colspan=2 align=\"center\"| gina\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Genitive\n! Singular\n! Plural\n|-\n|First person|| align=\"center\"| tsi, tsi-yi || align=\"center\"| tig-i\n|-\n|Second person|| align=\"center\"| nu, ni-yi || align=\"center\"| ? nig-i\n|-\n|Third person|| colspan=2 align=\"center\"| (gina-yi)\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Accusative\n! Singular\n! Plural\n|-\n|First person|| align=\"center\"| t\u0259n-da || align=\"center\"| (to\u0294-da)\n|-\n|Second person|| align=\"center\"| n\u0259n-da || align=\"center\"| (no\u0294-da)\n|-\n|Third person|| colspan=2 align=\"center\"| gin-da\n|}\n\nOther case suffixes include '''-ma''' \"together with\", '''-lage''' \"for\", '''-\u0259na''' \"from\", '''-ga, -g\u0259''' \"at, in\".\n\nThere are also [[demonstrative pronoun]]s '''na''' and '''ta'''. Although it is not clear what the difference between them is, it may be [[animacy]].\n\nSubjects may be marked on the verb, though when they are, they may either be prefixed or suffixed. An example with ''am'' \"eat\", which is more regular than many verbs, in the present tense (''-\u0259n'') is,\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! am \"eat\"\n! Singular\n! Plural\n|-\n|First person|| align=\"center\"| t-\u0259m-\u0259n || align=\"center\"| t-\u0259m-da-n\n|-\n|Second person|| align=\"center\"| n-\u0259m-\u0259n || align=\"center\"| n-\u0259m-da-n\n|-\n|Third person|| align=\"center\"| g-\u0259m-\u0259n || align=\"center\"| g-\u0259m-da-n\n|}\n\nOther verbs may have a prefix '''ts-''' in the first person, or zero in the third.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Wiktionary:Appendix:Kusunda word list|Kusunda word list]] (Wiktionary)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Reinhard, Johan and Sueyoshi Toba. (1970): ''A preliminary linguistic analysis and vocabulary of the Kusunda language''. Summer Institute of Linguistics and Tribhuvan University, Kathmandu.[http://languageserver.uni-graz.at/ls/book?id=2632]\n* Toba, Sueyoshi. 2000. ''Kusunda wordlists viewed diachronically''. Journal of Nationalities of Nepal 3(5): 87-91.[http://www.ethnologue.com/show_work.asp?id=43518]\n* Toba, Sueyoshi. 2000. ''The Kusunda language revisited after 30 years''. Journal of Nationalities of Nepal 3(5): 92-94.[http://www.ethnologue.com/show_work.asp?id=43519]\n* Watters, David E. 2005. ''Kusunda: a typological isolate in South Asia''. In Yogendra Yadava, Govinda Bhattarai, Ram Raj Lohani, Balaram Prasain and Krishna Parajuli (eds.), Contemporary issues in Nepalese linguistics p.&nbsp;375-396. Kathmandu: Linguistic Society of Nepal.\n* Watters, David E. 2006. \"Notes on Kusunda Grammar: A Language Isolate of Nepal\".[https://web.archive.org/web/20100622014718/http://www.linguistics.ucsb.edu/HimalayanLinguistics/grammars/2006/HLA03_Watters.pdf] ''Himalayan Linguistics Archive'' 3. (2006) 1-182.\n* Rana, B.K. ''Significance of Kusundas and their language in the Trans-Himalayan Region''. Mother Tongue. Journal of the Association for the Study of Language in Prehistory (Boston) IX, 2006, 212-218\n* Donohue, Mark, & Bhoj Raj Gautam. 2013. \"Evidence and Stance in Kusunda\". ''Nepalese Linguistics'' 28: 38-47.[http://papuan.linguistics.anu.edu.au/Donohue/downloads/Donohue_Gautam_2013_Kusunda_Evidentiality.pdf]\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-17537845 \"Nepal's mystery language on the verge of extinction\"], Bimal Gautum, [[BBC]], 12 May 2012\n* [http://listserv.emich.edu/cgi-bin/wa?A2=ind0410&L=endangered-languages-l&P=439 ''Kusunda language does not fall in any family: Study'', Himalayan News Service, Lalitpur, October 10, 2004]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070928030703/http://www.southasiabibliography.de/Bibliography/Kusunda__Banaraj__Myahak_/kusunda__banaraj__myahak_.html Partial bibliography]\n* [http://www.southasiabibliography.de/index.html Portal to Asian Internet Resources (Project). ''Bibliography for Seldom Studied and Endangered South Asian Languages''. Germany: John Peterson].\n* [http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:7HbGd2OInk8J:lloyd.emich.edu/cgi-bin/wa%3FA3%3Dind0103%26L%3Dling-amerindia%26P%3D49137%26E%3D2%26B%3D------%253D_NextPart_000_162c_198c_e16%26N%3DKusund~1.doc%26T%3Dapplication%252Fmsword+kusunda+Tribhuvan+University&hl=en&ct=clnk&cd=6&gl=us Rana, B.K. ''A Short note on Kusunda language.'' Janajati 2/4, 2001.]\n* [http://www.people.fas.harvard.edu/~witzel/kusunda.htm Rana, B.K., Linguistic Society of Nepal ''New Materials on Kusunda Language'', Presented to the Fourth Round Table International Conference on Ethnogenesis of South and Central Asia, Harvard University, Cambridge MA, USA. May 11-13, 2002]\n* [http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:w65I3i0DiWkJ:nipforum.org/Harvard_ASLIP_Kusunda_Paper_2006.pdf+kusunda+Tribhuvan+University&hl=en&ct=clnk&cd=5&gl=us Rana, B.K., ''Significance of Kusundas and Their Language in the Trans-Himalayan Region'', Harvard University, Cambridge, MA, October 21-22, 2006]\n* [http://escholarship.org/uc/item/83v8d1wv Watters, David. ''Notes on Kusunda Grammar: A language isolate of Nepal.'' Himalayan Linguistics Archive 3. 1-182, 2006]\n*{{Cite web\n| title = Obscure language isolate will die with this woman\n| work = The Hot Word - Hot & Trending Words Daily Blog at Dictionary.com\n| accessdate = 2012-08-02\n| date = 2012-06-03\n| url = http://hotword.dictionary.com/kusunda/\n}}\n* [http://kusunda.linguistics.anu.edu.au/ Kusunda linguistics (ANU)]\n\n{{Languages of Nepal}}\n{{Languages of South Asia}}\n{{Language families}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kusunda Language}}\n[[Category:Languages of Nepal]]\n[[Category:Kusunda language]]\n[[Category:Language isolates of Asia]]\n[[Category:Endangered language isolates]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox language\n| name = Kusunda\n| altname = Ban Raja\n| nativename = ''mihaq''\n| states = [[Nepal]]\n| region = [[Gandaki Zone]]\n| ethnicity = 270 Kusunda (2011 census)\n| extinct = \n| ref = \n| familycolor = Isolate\n| family = [[Language isolate]]\n| iso3 = kgg\n| glotto = kusu1250\n| glottorefname = Kusunda\n| map = Kusunda_language.png\n| mapcaption = Ethnologue locations: (west) [[Dang Deukhuri District|Dang]] and [[Pyuthan District|Pyuthan]] districts (dark grey) within [[Rapti Zone]]; (center) [[Tanahu District]] within [[Gandaki Zone]]<br>EndangeredLanguages.com location: red<br>[[World Atlas of Language Structures|WALS]] location: purple ([[Gorkha District]])\n| notice = IPA\n}}\n\n'''Kusunda''' (Kusanda) is a [[language isolate]] spoken by a handful of people in western and central [[Nepal]]. It has only recently been described in any detail.\n\n==Rediscovery==\nFor decades the Kusunda language was thought to be on the verge of extinction, with little hope of ever knowing it well. The little material that could be gleaned from the memories of former speakers suggested that the language was an isolate, but without much evidence either way it was often classified along with its neighbors as [[Tibeto-Burman languages|Tibeto-Burman]]. However, in 2004 three [[Kusunda people|Kusunda]]s, Gyani Maya Sen, Prem Bahadur Shahi and Kamala Singh,<ref name=3Kusundas>{{cite web |url=http://listserv.emich.edu/cgi-bin/wa?A2=ind0410&L=endangered-languages-l&P=439 |title=Kusunda language does not fall in any family: Study |accessdate=2007-09-12 |last=Rana |first=B.K. |date=2004-10-12 |work=email with pasted news article |publisher=Himalayan News Service, Lalitpur, 2004-10-10 }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> were brought to [[Kathmandu]] for help with citizenship papers. There, members of [[Tribhuvan University]] discovered that one of them, a native of Sakhi VDC in southern [[Rolpa District]], was a fluent speaker of the language. Several of her relatives were also discovered to be fluent. There are now known to be at least seven or eight fluent speakers of the language, the youngest in her thirties.<ref name=\"Watters2006\"/> However, the language is [[moribund language|moribund]], with no children learning it, as all Kusunda speakers have married outside their ethnicity.<ref name=\"Watters2006\">Watters, David E. 2005. ''Kusunda: a typological isolate in South Asia.'' In Yogendra Yadava, Govinda Bhattarai, Ram Raj Lohani, Balaram Prasain and Krishna Parajuli (eds.), Contemporary issues in Nepalese linguistics p.&nbsp;375-396. Kathmandu: Linguistic Society of Nepal.</ref>\n\nIt was presumed that with the death of Rajamama Kusunda on 19 April 2018 the language went extinct, though Gyani Maiya Sen could be the only surviving speaker.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2018-04-19/rajamama-lone-kusunda-language-speaker-dies.html|title=Rajamama, lone Kusunda language speaker, dies|access-date=2018-06-18|language=en}}</ref>\n\nGyani Maiya Sen and her sister Kamala Kusunda who can speak the language fluently, together with author and researcher Uday Raj Aaley, have been teaching interested children and adults the Kusunda language. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2019/01/04/resuscitating-dying-kusunda-language|title=Resuscitating dying Kusunda language|last=|first=|date=4 January 2019|website=The Kathmandu Post|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nAaley, the facilitator and Kusunda language teacher, has authored the book \"Kusunda Tribe and Dictionary\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/art-entertainment/2017/08/01/book-that-traces-kusunda-tribes-history-hits-shelves|title=Book that traces Kusunda tribe's history hits shelves|last=|first=|date=1 August 2017|website=The Kathmandu Post|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref> The book has a compilation of over 1000 words from the Kusunda language. \n\n==Classification==\n[[David E. Watters|Watters]] (2005) published a mid-sized grammatical description of the language, plus vocabulary, which shows that Kusunda is indeed a language isolate, not just genealogically but also lexically, grammatically, and phonologically distinct from its neighbors. It appears that Kusunda is a remnant of the languages spoken in northern India before the influx of Tibeto-Burman- and [[Indo-Iranian languages|Indo-Iranian]]-speaking peoples, however it is not classified as a [[Munda languages|Munda]] or a [[Dravidian languages|Dravidian]] language. It thus joins [[Burushaski]], [[Nihali]] and (potentially) the substrate of the [[Vedda language]] in the list of South Asian languages which do not fall into the main categories of Indo-European, Dravidian, [[Sino-Tibetan languages|Sino-Tibetan]] and [[Austroasiatic languages|Austroasiatic]].\n\nBefore the recent discovery of active Kusunda speakers, there were several attempts to link the language to an established language family. B. K. Rana (2002) maintained that Kusunda is a [[Tibeto-Burman languages|Tibeto-Burman language]] as traditionally classified. Others have linked it to [[Munda languages|Munda]] (see [[David E. Watters|Watters]] 2005); [[Yeniseian languages|Yeniseian]] (Gurov 1989); [[Burushaski language|Burushaski]] and [[Caucasian languages|Caucasian]] (Reinhard and Toba 1970; this would be a variant of Gurov's proposal if [[Sino-Caucasian]] is accepted); the [[Nihali language|Nihali]] isolate in central India (Fleming 1996, Whitehouse 1997); and again with Nihali, as part of the [[Indo-Pacific languages|Indo-Pacific]] hypothesis (Whitehouse et al. 2004<ref>{{Cite journal\n| title = Kusunda: An Indo-Pacific language in Nepal\n| journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America\n| date = 2004-04-13\n| volume = 101\n| pages = 5692\u20135695                                     \n| url = http://www.pnas.org/content/101/15/5692.full\n|author1=Paul Whitehouse |author2=Timothy Usher | author3-link = Merritt Ruhlen\n|author3=Merritt Ruhlen |author4=William S.-Y. Wang | doi = 10.1073/pnas.0400233101\n| pmid = 15056764\n| issue = 15\n| pmc = 397480\n}}</ref>).\n\n[[John McWhorter]] supports [[Merritt Ruhlen]]'s argument of a relationship between Kusuna and the [[Oko-Juwoi language|Juwoi]] language spoken on the [[Andaman Islands]].<ref>John McWhorter, ''[[The Great Courses]]: Language Families of the World'', episode 14, \"Indian Languages That Aren't Indo-European\"</ref>\n\n==Phonology==\n\n===Vowels===\nPhonetically, Kusunda has six vowels in two [[vowel harmony|harmonic]] groups, which are arguably three vowels phonemically: a word will normally have vowels from the upper (pink) or lower (green) set, but not both simultaneously.  There are very few words that consistently have upper or lower vowels; most words may be pronounced either way, though those with [[uvular consonant]]s require the lower set (as in many languages). There are a few words with no uvular consonants that still bar such dual pronunciations, though these generally only feature the distinction in careful enunciation.<ref name=Watters/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|+Kusunda vowels\n! align=\"center\"| Vowels\n! align=\"center\"|[[Front vowel|Front]]\n! align=\"center\"|[[Central vowel|Central]]\n! align=\"center\"|[[Back vowel|Back]]\n|-\n|-\n|align=\"center\" |[[Close vowel|Close]]|| align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#ffcccc\" | {{IPA|i}} || || align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#ffcccc\"|{{IPA|u}}\n|-\n|align=\"center\" | [[Mid vowel|Mid]]|| align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#ccffcc\"| {{IPA|e}} || align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#ffcccc\"|{{IPA|\u0259}} || align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#ccffcc\"|{{IPA|o}}\n|-\n|align=\"center\" | [[Open vowel|Open]] || || align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#ccffcc\"| {{IPA|a}} || \n|}\n\n===Consonants===\nKusunda consonants seem to only contrast the active articulator, not where that articulator makes contact. For example, apical consonants may be [[dental consonant|dental]], [[alveolar consonant|alveolar]], [[retroflex consonant|retroflex]], or [[palatal consonant|palatal]]: {{IPA|/t/}} is dental {{IPA|[t\u032a]}} before {{IPA|/i/}}, alveolar {{IPA|[t\u0347]}} before {{IPA|/e, \u0259, u/}}, retroflex {{IPA|[\u0288]}} before {{IPA|/o, a/}}, and palatal {{IPA|[c]}} when there is a following uvular, as in {{IPA|[coq]}} ~ {{IPA|[t\u0347ok]}} ('we').<ref name=Watters/>\n\nIn addition, many consonants vary between [[stop consonant|stops]] and [[fricative consonant|fricative]]s; for instance, {{IPA|/p/}} seems to surface as {{IPA|[b]}} between vowels, while {{IPA|/b/}} surfaces as {{IPA|[\u03b2]}} in the same environment. [[Aspiration (phonetics)|Aspiration]] appears to be recent to the language. Kusunda also lacks the [[retroflex consonant]] phonemes common to the region, and is unique in the region in having [[uvular consonant]]s.<ref name=Watters/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+Consonants\n!\n! [[Labial consonant|Labial]]\n! [[Coronal consonant|Coronal]]\n! [[Palatal consonant|Palatal]]\n! [[Velar consonant|Velar]]\n! [[Uvular consonant|Uvular]]\n! [[Glottal consonant|Glottal]]\n|- \n| [[Nasal consonant|Nasal]]|| '''{{IPA|m}}''' || '''{{IPA|n}}''' || || '''{{IPA|\u014b}}''' || '''{{IPA|\u0274\u0295}}''' || \n|- \n| [[Plosive consonant|Plosive]]|| {{IPA|'''p~b<br>b~\u03b2'''<br>(p\u02b0 b\u02b1)}} || {{IPA|'''t~d<br>d'''<br>(t\u02b0 d\u02b1)}} || || {{IPA|'''k~\u0261<br>\u0261~\u0263'''<br>(k\u02b0~x \u0261\u02b1)}} || {{IPA|'''q~\u0262'''<br>(q\u02b0)}} || {{IPA|'''\u0294'''<br>&nbsp;}}\n|- \n| [[Affricate consonant|Affricate]]|| || {{IPA|'''ts<br>dz'''<br>(ts\u02b0 dz\u02b1)}} || || || || \n|- \n| [[Fricative consonant|Fricative]]|| || '''{{IPA|s}}''' || || || rowspan=2| '''{{IPA|\u0281~\u0295}}''' || rowspan=2| '''{{IPA|h}}'''\n|- \n| [[Approximant consonant|Approximant]]|| '''{{IPA|w}}''' || '''{{IPA|l}}''' || '''{{IPA|j}}''' || \n|- \n| [[Flap consonant|Flap]] || || '''{{IPA|\u027e}}''' || || || ||  \n|}\n\n{{IPA|[\u0295]}} does not occur initially, and {{IPA|[\u014b]}} only occurs at the end of a syllable, unlike in neighboring languages. {{IPA|[\u0274\u0295]}} only occurs between vowels; it may be |{{IPA|\u014b+\u0295}}|.<ref name=Watters/>\n\n==Pronouns==\n\nKusunda has several cases, marked on nouns and pronouns three of which are [[nominative]] (Kusunda, unlike its neighbors, has no [[ergativity]]), [[genitive]], and [[accusative case|accusative]] [[Grammatical person|persons]].<ref name=Watters>Watters (2005)</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Nominative\n! Singular\n! Plural\n|-\n|First person|| align=\"center\"| tsi || align=\"center\"| tok\n|-\n|Second person|| align=\"center\"| nu || align=\"center\"| nok\n|-\n|Third person|| colspan=2 align=\"center\"| gina\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Genitive\n! Singular\n! Plural\n|-\n|First person|| align=\"center\"| tsi, tsi-yi || align=\"center\"| tig-i\n|-\n|Second person|| align=\"center\"| nu, ni-yi || align=\"center\"| ? nig-i\n|-\n|Third person|| colspan=2 align=\"center\"| (gina-yi)\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Accusative\n! Singular\n! Plural\n|-\n|First person|| align=\"center\"| t\u0259n-da || align=\"center\"| (to\u0294-da)\n|-\n|Second person|| align=\"center\"| n\u0259n-da || align=\"center\"| (no\u0294-da)\n|-\n|Third person|| colspan=2 align=\"center\"| gin-da\n|}\n\nOther case suffixes include '''-ma''' \"together with\", '''-lage''' \"for\", '''-\u0259na''' \"from\", '''-ga, -g\u0259''' \"at, in\".\n\nThere are also [[demonstrative pronoun]]s '''na''' and '''ta'''. Although it is not clear what the difference between them is, it may be [[animacy]].\n\nSubjects may be marked on the verb, though when they are, they may either be prefixed or suffixed. An example with ''am'' \"eat\", which is more regular than many verbs, in the present tense (''-\u0259n'') is,\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! am \"eat\"\n! Singular\n! Plural\n|-\n|First person|| align=\"center\"| t-\u0259m-\u0259n || align=\"center\"| t-\u0259m-da-n\n|-\n|Second person|| align=\"center\"| n-\u0259m-\u0259n || align=\"center\"| n-\u0259m-da-n\n|-\n|Third person|| align=\"center\"| g-\u0259m-\u0259n || align=\"center\"| g-\u0259m-da-n\n|}\n\nOther verbs may have a prefix '''ts-''' in the first person, or zero in the third.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Wiktionary:Appendix:Kusunda word list|Kusunda word list]] (Wiktionary)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Reinhard, Johan and Sueyoshi Toba. (1970): ''A preliminary linguistic analysis and vocabulary of the Kusunda language''. Summer Institute of Linguistics and Tribhuvan University, Kathmandu.[http://languageserver.uni-graz.at/ls/book?id=2632]\n* Toba, Sueyoshi. 2000. ''Kusunda wordlists viewed diachronically''. Journal of Nationalities of Nepal 3(5): 87-91.[http://www.ethnologue.com/show_work.asp?id=43518]\n* Toba, Sueyoshi. 2000. ''The Kusunda language revisited after 30 years''. Journal of Nationalities of Nepal 3(5): 92-94.[http://www.ethnologue.com/show_work.asp?id=43519]\n* Watters, David E. 2005. ''Kusunda: a typological isolate in South Asia''. In Yogendra Yadava, Govinda Bhattarai, Ram Raj Lohani, Balaram Prasain and Krishna Parajuli (eds.), Contemporary issues in Nepalese linguistics p.&nbsp;375-396. Kathmandu: Linguistic Society of Nepal.\n* Watters, David E. 2006. \"Notes on Kusunda Grammar: A Language Isolate of Nepal\".[https://web.archive.org/web/20100622014718/http://www.linguistics.ucsb.edu/HimalayanLinguistics/grammars/2006/HLA03_Watters.pdf] ''Himalayan Linguistics Archive'' 3. (2006) 1-182.\n* Rana, B.K. ''Significance of Kusundas and their language in the Trans-Himalayan Region''. Mother Tongue. Journal of the Association for the Study of Language in Prehistory (Boston) IX, 2006, 212-218\n* Donohue, Mark, & Bhoj Raj Gautam. 2013. \"Evidence and Stance in Kusunda\". ''Nepalese Linguistics'' 28: 38-47.[http://papuan.linguistics.anu.edu.au/Donohue/downloads/Donohue_Gautam_2013_Kusunda_Evidentiality.pdf]\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-17537845 \"Nepal's mystery language on the verge of extinction\"], Bimal Gautum, [[BBC]], 12 May 2012\n* [http://listserv.emich.edu/cgi-bin/wa?A2=ind0410&L=endangered-languages-l&P=439 ''Kusunda language does not fall in any family: Study'', Himalayan News Service, Lalitpur, October 10, 2004]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070928030703/http://www.southasiabibliography.de/Bibliography/Kusunda__Banaraj__Myahak_/kusunda__banaraj__myahak_.html Partial bibliography]\n* [http://www.southasiabibliography.de/index.html Portal to Asian Internet Resources (Project). ''Bibliography for Seldom Studied and Endangered South Asian Languages''. Germany: John Peterson].\n* [http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:7HbGd2OInk8J:lloyd.emich.edu/cgi-bin/wa%3FA3%3Dind0103%26L%3Dling-amerindia%26P%3D49137%26E%3D2%26B%3D------%253D_NextPart_000_162c_198c_e16%26N%3DKusund~1.doc%26T%3Dapplication%252Fmsword+kusunda+Tribhuvan+University&hl=en&ct=clnk&cd=6&gl=us Rana, B.K. ''A Short note on Kusunda language.'' Janajati 2/4, 2001.]\n* [http://www.people.fas.harvard.edu/~witzel/kusunda.htm Rana, B.K., Linguistic Society of Nepal ''New Materials on Kusunda Language'', Presented to the Fourth Round Table International Conference on Ethnogenesis of South and Central Asia, Harvard University, Cambridge MA, USA. May 11-13, 2002]\n* [http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:w65I3i0DiWkJ:nipforum.org/Harvard_ASLIP_Kusunda_Paper_2006.pdf+kusunda+Tribhuvan+University&hl=en&ct=clnk&cd=5&gl=us Rana, B.K., ''Significance of Kusundas and Their Language in the Trans-Himalayan Region'', Harvard University, Cambridge, MA, October 21-22, 2006]\n* [http://escholarship.org/uc/item/83v8d1wv Watters, David. ''Notes on Kusunda Grammar: A language isolate of Nepal.'' Himalayan Linguistics Archive 3. 1-182, 2006]\n*{{Cite web\n| title = Obscure language isolate will die with this woman\n| work = The Hot Word - Hot & Trending Words Daily Blog at Dictionary.com\n| accessdate = 2012-08-02\n| date = 2012-06-03\n| url = http://hotword.dictionary.com/kusunda/\n}}\n* [http://kusunda.linguistics.anu.edu.au/ Kusunda linguistics (ANU)]\n\n{{Languages of Nepal}}\n{{Languages of South Asia}}\n{{Language families}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kusunda Language}}\n[[Category:Languages of Nepal]]\n[[Category:Kusunda language]]\n[[Category:Language isolates of Asia]]\n[[Category:Endangered language isolates]]\n", "name_user": "Bondegezou", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eClassification", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kusunda_language"}
{"title_page": "Banded yellow robin", "text_new": "{{short description|Species of songbird native to New Guinea}}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = Banded yellow robin\n| image = Poecilodryas placens - The Birds of New Guinea (2).jpg\n| image_caption = Illustration by [[John Gould]] and [[William Matthew Hart|W. Hart]]\n| status = NT\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/106005495/0 |title=''Poecilodryas placens'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=16 July 2012|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Gennaeodryas\n| parent_authority = [[Gregory Mathews|Mathews]], 1920\n| species = placens\n| authority = ([[Edward Pierson Ramsay|Ramsay, E.P.]], 1879)\n| synonyms =''Poecilodryas placens''\n}}\n\nThe '''banded yellow robin''' or '''olive-yellow robin''' (''Gennaeodryas placens'') is a species of [[bird]] in the Australasian robin family [[Petroicidae]] that is found in [[New Guinea]]. It is the only species in the genus '''''Gennaeodryas'''''. Its natural [[habitat]]s are [[subtropical or tropical moist lowland forest]] and subtropical or tropical moist [[montane forest]].\nIt is threatened by [[habitat loss]]. It has a high mortality rate due to its inability to traverse across a matrix.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scopus.com/record/display.uri?eid=2-s2.0-84872453741&origin=resultslist&sort=plf-f&src=s&st1=banded+yellow+robins&st2=&sid=e4c648ab7582cd83a2cea40f4ace6076&sot=b&sdt=b&sl=35&s=TITLE-ABS-KEY(banded+yellow+robins)&relpos=0&citeCnt=5&searchTerm=|title=Scopus preview - Scopus - Welcome to Scopus|last=|first=|date=|website=www.scopus.com|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-11-07}}</ref>\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe banded yellow robin was described by the Australian zoologist, [[Edward Pierson Ramsay]], in 1879, from a specimen collected in southeastern [[New Guinea]]. He coined the [[binomial name]] ''Eopsaltria placens''.<ref>{{ cite journal | last=Ramsay | first=E.P. | author-link=Edward Pierson Ramsay | year=1879 | title=Contributions to the zoology of New Guinea. Parts I and II | journal=Proceedings of the Linnean Society of New South Wales | volume=3 | pages=241-305 [272] | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/6456651 | doi=10.5962/bhl.part.22241 }}</ref> The species was subsequently placed in the genus ''Poecilodryas''.<ref>{{ cite book | editor1-last=Mayr | editor1-first=Ernst | editor1-link=Ernst Mayr | editor2-last=Cottrell | editor2-first=G. William | year=1986 | title=Check-list of Birds of the World | volume=Volume 11 | publisher=Museum of Comparative Zoology | place=Cambridge, Massachusetts | page=576 | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/14484277 }}</ref> It was moved to the resurrected genus ''Gennaeodryas'', based on the results of a [[molecular phylogenetic]] study published in 2011.<ref>{{ cite journal | last1=Christidis | first1=L. | last2=Irestedt | first2=M. | last3=Rowe | first3=D. | last4=Boles | first4=W.E. | last5=Norman | first5=J.A. | year=2011 | title=Mitochondrial and nuclear DNA phylogenies reveal a complex evolutionary history in the Australasian robins (Passeriformes: Petroicidae) | journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution | volume=61 | issue=3 | pages=726\u2013738 | doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2011.08.014 | pmid=21867765 }}</ref><ref name=ioc>{{cite web| editor1-last=Gill | editor1-first=Frank | editor1-link=Frank Gill (ornithologist) | editor2-last=Donsker | editor2-first=David | year=2019 | title=Australasian robins, rockfowl, rockjumpers, Rail-babbler | work=World Bird List Version 9.2 | url=https://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/au_robins/ | publisher=International Ornithologists' Union | accessdate=17 June 2019 }}</ref> The genus ''Gennaeodryas'' had been introduced by the Australian ornithologist, [[Gregory Mathews]], in 1920.<ref>{{ cite book | last=Mathews | first=Gregory | author-link=Gregory Mathews | year=1920 | title=Birds of Australia | volume=Volume 8 | location=London | publisher=Witherby | page=186 | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/53480695 }}</ref> The genus name combines the [[Ancient Greek]] ''gennaios'' 'noble' or 'high-born' with ''dryad'' 'tree-nymph'.<ref>{{cite web | last=Jobling | first=J.A. | year=2019 | title=''Gennaeodryas'' | editor1-last=del Hoyo | editor1-first=J. | editor2-last=Elliott | editor2-first=A. | editor3-last=Sargatal | editor3-first=J. | editor4-last=Christie | editor4-first=D.A. | editor5-last=de Juana | editor5-first=E. | work=Handbook of the Birds of the World Alive: Key to Scientific Names in Ornithology | publisher=Lynx Edicions | url=https://www.hbw.com/dictionary/definition/gennaeodryas | accessdate=17 June 2019 }}</ref> The specific epithet ''placens'' is the Latin word for 'charming' or 'pleasing'.<ref>{{cite web | last=Jobling | first=J.A. | year=2019 | title=placens-placentis | editor1-last=del Hoyo | editor1-first=J. | editor2-last=Elliott | editor2-first=A. | editor3-last=Sargatal | editor3-first=J. | editor4-last=Christie | editor4-first=D.A. | editor5-last=de Juana | editor5-first=E. | work=Handbook of the Birds of the World Alive:  Key to Scientific Names in Ornithology | publisher=Lynx Edicions | url=https://www.hbw.com/dictionary/definition/placens-placentis | accessdate=17 June 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* del Hoyo, J.; Elliot, A. & Christie D. (editors). (2007). ''[[Handbook of the Birds of the World]]''. Volume 12: Picathartes to Tits and Chickadees. Lynx Edicions. {{ISBN|978-84-96553-42-2}}\n\n{{Petroicidae}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1590184}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:robin, yellow, banded}}\n[[Category:Birds of New Guinea]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1879|banded yellow robin]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n\n\n{{Petroicidae-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Species of songbird native to New Guinea}}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = Banded yellow robin\n| image = Poecilodryas placens - The Birds of New Guinea (2).jpg\n| image_caption = Illustration by [[John Gould]] and [[William Matthew Hart|W. Hart]]\n| status = NT\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/106005495/0 |title=''Poecilodryas placens'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=16 July 2012|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Gennaeodryas\n| parent_authority = [[Gregory Mathews|Mathews]], 1920\n| species = placens\n| authority = ([[Edward Pierson Ramsay|Ramsay, E.P.]], 1879)\n| synonyms =''Poecilodryas placens''\n}}\n\nThe '''banded yellow robin''' or '''olive-yellow robin''' (''Gennaeodryas placens'') is a species of [[bird]] in the Australasian robin family [[Petroicidae]] that is found in [[New Guinea]]. It is the only species in the genus '''''Gennaeodryas'''''. Its natural [[habitat]]s are [[subtropical or tropical moist lowland forest]] and subtropical or tropical moist [[montane forest]].\nIt is threatened by [[habitat loss]]. It has a high mortality rate due to its inability to traverse across a matrix.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scopus.com/record/display.uri?eid=2-s2.0-84872453741&origin=resultslist&sort=plf-f&src=s&st1=banded+yellow+robins&st2=&sid=e4c648ab7582cd83a2cea40f4ace6076&sot=b&sdt=b&sl=35&s=TITLE-ABS-KEY(banded+yellow+robins)&relpos=0&citeCnt=5&searchTerm=|title=Scopus preview - Scopus - Welcome to Scopus|last=|first=|date=|website=www.scopus.com|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-11-07}}</ref>\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe banded yellow robin was described by the Australian zoologist [[Edward Pierson Ramsay]] in 1879 from a specimen collected in southeastern [[New Guinea]]. He coined the [[binomial name]] ''Eopsaltria placens''.<ref>{{ cite journal | last=Ramsay | first=E.P. | author-link=Edward Pierson Ramsay | year=1879 | title=Contributions to the zoology of New Guinea. Parts I and II | journal=Proceedings of the Linnean Society of New South Wales | volume=3 | pages=241-305 [272] | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/6456651 | doi=10.5962/bhl.part.22241 }}</ref> The species was subsequently placed in the genus ''Poecilodryas''.<ref>{{ cite book | editor1-last=Mayr | editor1-first=Ernst | editor1-link=Ernst Mayr | editor2-last=Cottrell | editor2-first=G. William | year=1986 | title=Check-list of Birds of the World | volume=Volume 11 | publisher=Museum of Comparative Zoology | place=Cambridge, Massachusetts | page=576 | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/14484277 }}</ref> It was moved to the resurrected genus ''Gennaeodryas'' based on the results of a [[molecular phylogenetic]] study published in 2011.<ref>{{ cite journal | last1=Christidis | first1=L. | last2=Irestedt | first2=M. | last3=Rowe | first3=D. | last4=Boles | first4=W.E. | last5=Norman | first5=J.A. | year=2011 | title=Mitochondrial and nuclear DNA phylogenies reveal a complex evolutionary history in the Australasian robins (Passeriformes: Petroicidae) | journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution | volume=61 | issue=3 | pages=726\u2013738 | doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2011.08.014 | pmid=21867765 }}</ref><ref name=ioc>{{cite web| editor1-last=Gill | editor1-first=Frank | editor1-link=Frank Gill (ornithologist) | editor2-last=Donsker | editor2-first=David | year=2019 | title=Australasian robins, rockfowl, rockjumpers, Rail-babbler | work=World Bird List Version 9.2 | url=https://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/au_robins/ | publisher=International Ornithologists' Union | accessdate=17 June 2019 }}</ref> The genus ''Gennaeodryas'' had been introduced by the Australian ornithologist [[Gregory Mathews]] in 1920.<ref>{{ cite book | last=Mathews | first=Gregory | author-link=Gregory Mathews | year=1920 | title=Birds of Australia | volume=Volume 8 | location=London | publisher=Witherby | page=186 | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/53480695 }}</ref> The genus name combines the [[Ancient Greek]] ''gennaios'' \"noble\" or \"high-born\" with ''dryad'' \"tree-nymph\".<ref>{{cite web | last=Jobli