lected Papers from the Fourth World Congress for Soviet and East European Studies, Harrogate, 1990 |editor-last=Graham |editor-first=Sheelagh Duffin |publisher=St. Martin's Press in association with the International Council for Soviet and East European Studies |location=New York |year=1992 |isbn=0-312-07990-7 |pages=164\u2013181 |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Pontius Pilate}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n*{{wikisource inline |list=\n** {{cite CE1913 |last=Barnes |first=Arthur Stapylton |wstitle=Pontius Pilate |volume=12|short=x |noicon=x}}\n** {{cite EB1911 |last=Innes |first=Alexander Taylor|wstitle=Pilate, Pontius |volume=21 |pages=602\u2013603|short=x |noicon=x}}\n}}\n* {{cite Jewish Encyclopedia  |last=Singer |first=Isidore |last2=Broyd\u00e9 |first2=Isaac|url=http://jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=312&letter=P&search=Pilate |title=Pilate, Pontius |volume=10 |pages=23\u201335 |short=x}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou|[[Roman administration of Judaea (AD 6\u2013135)|Roman Rulers of Judaea]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Valerius Gratus]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Roman administration of Judaea (AD 6\u2013135)|Prefect]] of [[Iudaea Province|Iudaea]]|years=26\u201336}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Marcellus, prefect of Judea|Marcellus]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{New Testament people}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pilate, Pontius}}\n[[Category:1st-century BC births]]\n[[Category:39 deaths]]\n[[Category:1st-century Romans]]\n[[Category:1st-century Christianity]]\n[[Category:1st-century Christian saints]]\n[[Category:1st-century Roman governors of Judea]]\n[[Category:Coptic Orthodox saints]]\n[[Category:Jews and Judaism in the Roman Empire]]\n[[Category:Ethiopian saints]]\n[[Category:Jesus and history]]\n[[Category:People in the canonical gospels]]\n[[Category:Roman governors of Judea]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Teramo]]\n[[Category:Pontii]]\n[[Category:Pontius Pilate| ]]\n[[Category:Ancient Romans who committed suicide]]\n[[Category:Ancient Roman saints]]\n", "name_user": "Mercury McKinnon", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLater legends:sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pontius_Pilate"}
{"title_page": "Bodo-Kachari peoples", "text_new": "{{About|group of ethnic peoples|the specific ethnic group|Bodo people}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n| group = Bodo-Kachari Peoples\n| native_name = Kachari\n| image = File:Kherai Dance of Assam.jpg\n| image_caption = Boro Kherai Dance\n| population = [[Circa|c.]] '''12\u201314&nbsp;million'''\n| region1 = [[Assam]]\n| pop1 = n/a\n| region2 = [[Tripura]]\n| pop2 = n/a\n| region3 = [[Meghalaya]]\n| pop3 = n/a\n| region4 = [[Arunachal Pradesh]]\n| pop4 = n/a\n| rels = '''Predominant''' {{hlist|[[Hinduism]] }}\n'''Minority''' {{hlist| [[Christianity]]| [[Animism]]}}\n| related = {{hlist | other [[Tibeto-Burman]] groups}}\n| native_name_lang = \n| languages = \n}}\n{{Culture of Assam}}\n'''Bodo-Kachari''' (also '''Kachari''',{{sfn|Endle|1911}} '''Bodo'''<ref name=\"jacobnote\"/>) is a generic term applied to a number of [[ethnic group]]s living predominantly in the [[Northeast India]]n state of [[Assam]], that speak [[Assamese language|Assamese]] and [[Tibeto-Burman languages]] and possibly have a shared ancestry. Although most of these groups spoke different forms of [[Boro-Garo languages]] in historical times, today a majority of them speak Assamese. \n\nThe [[Bodo language]], one of the languages in the Boro-Garo group, has been recognised as an eighth scheduled Indian language since 2004. They are part of the [[Tibeto-Burman and Tai peoples of Assam|Tibeto-Burman speaking community]] of Assam.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Govt. of India|first1=Ministry of Home Affairs|title=Eight Schedules|url=http://mha.nic.in/hindi/sites/upload_files/mhahindi/files/pdf/Eighth_Schedule.pdf|website=mha.nic.in|access-date=13 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305010536/http://mha.nic.in/hindi/sites/upload_files/mhahindi/files/pdf/Eighth_Schedule.pdf#|archive-date=5 March 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThey are considered to have reached the Brahmaputra valley via Tibet and settled in the foothills of the eastern Himalayan range which includes the whole of Assam, Tripura, North Bengal and parts of Bangladesh. The belief that Bodo-Kacharis were early settlers of the river valleys is taken from the fact that most of the rivers in the Brahmaputra valley today carry Tibeto-Burman names\u2014Dibang, Dihang, Dikhou, Dihing, Doiyang, Doigrung etc.\u2014where ''Di/Doi-'' means water in Boro-Garo languages.\n\nSome of the groups, such as Moran and Saraniya consider themselves as lower-caste Hindus under [[Ekasarana Dharma]]. Other groups, such as the Garo, Rabha, Lalung and Hajong having been isolated from the parental stock, have established separate identities. With the exception of the Garo, which is still a matrilineal society, the other groups do not follow rules of matrilineal society.\n\nThe Mech in Western Assam, the Boro in central Assam; the Dimasa in Dima Hasao District (DHD) formerly North Cachar Hills, Cachar district and Nagaland state and the Sonowal and Thengal in the eastern part of the Brahmaputra now represent the Kachari.\n\n==Etymologies==\n===Bodo===\nThe term ''Bodo'' was published by [[Brian Houghton Hodgson|Hodgson]] in 1847, to denote the [[Mech tribe|Mech]] people of Darjeeling district and their language,<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{harv|Narjinari|2000|p=4}}{{harv|Grierson|1903|p=1}}</ref> though this term was never used in the sources of history of Assam.<ref>\"The term Bodo was first used by Brian H Hodgson in his book ''On the Koch, Bodo and Dhimal Tribes'' in 1847 and no reference of the term is seen in any sources in the history of Assam.\" {{harvcol|Bathari|2014|p=14}}</ref> [[George Abraham Grierson|Grierson]] took this term to denote a section of the Assam-Burma group of the [[Tibeto-Burman]] speakers of the [[Sino-Tibetan languages|Sino-Tibetan]] speech family,{{sfn|Choudhury|2007|p=1}} which included the languages of (1) Mech; (2) Rabha; (3) Lalung (Tiwa); (4) Dimasa (Hills Kachari); (5) Garo (6) Tiprasa and (7) Chutiya.{{sfn|Grierson|1903|p=2}} Over time, for anthropological and linguistic purposes, ''Bodo'' came to denote all people in Nepal, India, and Bangladesh that spoke related languages now or in the past, or claimed a shared ancestry.<ref>\"[I]t seems that the term Bodo is used particularly to denote sections of people having an agnatic relationship in terms of speech practices and a strong sense of shared ancestry. This term the Bodo is more anthropological in its usage.\" {{harvcol|Bathari|2014|p=14}}</ref> This umbrella-group includes such sub-groups as Mech in Bengal and Nepal; Boros (also confusingly called Bodo), Dimasa, Chutia, Sonowal, Rabha, Tiwa in Assam, and the Kokborok people in Tripura and Bangladesh.<ref>{{harvcol|Bathari|2014|p=14}}</ref><ref name=\"jacobnote\">\"The term Bodo is also used to denote a large number of tribes\u2014 The Bodo people, The Garos of Meghalaya, Tiprasa of Tripura, Koch, Rabha, Lalung, Dimasa, Hajong, Chutia, Deuri and Moran of Assam and other parts of Northeast (M N Brahma, \"The Bodo-Kacharis of Assam---A brief Introduction) 1:1 (1983) p52\" {{harv|George|1994|p=878}}</ref> This is in contrast to popular and socio-political usage, where Bodo denotes the politically dominant sub-group\u2014the ''Boros''\u2014in the [[Bodoland|Bodoland Territorial Autonomous Districts]].<ref>\"In present-day socio-political terminology, the Bodo means the plains tribes of the Brahmaputra Valley known earlier as Bodo-Kachari.\" {{harv|Choudhury|2007|p=1}}</ref><ref>\"The media at the regional and national level; officials at the Centre and the state political parties of all hues and the people, in general, have accepted what may be termed as a contraction of the original denotion.\" {{harv|Choudhury|2007|p=1}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the word \"Bodo\" was used as an umbrella term during the British period, the term generally stands for ''man'' in some of the cognate languages (Boro:''Boro''; Tripuri:''Borok'') but not in others (Garo:''Mande''; Karbi:''Arlen'').<ref>\"One section of the same stock, Garo, a Tribe called themselves \u201cMande\u201d means Man: another word Arleng (Karbi) is popularly used among Karbis, which literally means Man.\" {{harvcol|Brahma|2008|pp=1\u20132}}</ref> According to historians, the word \"Bodo\" is derived from the Tibetan ''Hbrogpa''.<ref>\"The inception of the term 'Boro' may be traced from a Tibetan word 'Hbrogpa' an inhabitant of steppes belongs to Mongolean race.\" {{harvcol|Brahma|2008|p=2}}</ref>\n\nThe umbrella name \"Bodo\" is resisted by numerically smaller groups such as the Dimasas.<ref>This has been viewed with contempt by several sections of the groups as a design by the Boros to establish their pre-dominance over numerically and otherwise weaker sections of the group. Most of the resistance has come from the Dimasas, who often accuse the Boros of appropriating the history and language of the Dimasas.{{harv|Bathari|2014|p=14-15}}</ref>\n\n===Kachari===\nOn the other hand, the term ''Kachari'' has been used through much of history to denote the same people.<ref>\"On the other hand, for the larger part of history, this group of people is referred to as Kacharis.\" {{harvcol|Bathari|2014|p=14}}</ref> One of the earliest usage can be found in the 16-th century [[Assamese language]] [[Bhagavat of Sankardev|Bhagavata]].<ref>Srimandbhagavat, skandha 2, H Dattabaruah and Co., Nalbari, pp-38: ''kiraTa kachhaari khaachi gaaro miri'' / ''yavana ka~Nka govaala'' /</ref>\nKachari is pronounced as Kachh\u0101ri or Koss\u0101ri. The origin of the name is most likely a self-designation ''korosa aris'' that is found in a very old Kachari song:<ref>{{harvcol|Mosahary|1983|p=47}}</ref>\n<poem>\n''Pra Ari, Korasa Ari''\n''Jong pari lari lari''\n(We are Korosa Aris, first-born sea race\nOur line is continuous)\n</poem>\n\n==Ethnic groups==\n\n=== Boro ===\n{{main|Boro people}}\nThe Boro people, also called Bodo, are found concentrated in the [[duars]] regions, north of [[Goalpara]] and [[Kamrup region|Kamrup]]. The origin of Kachari term was unknown to Boro themselves, but known to others. They call themselves as Boro, Bada, Bodo, Barafisa. Barafisa translated as Children of the Bara.\n\n===Mech===\n{{main|Mech tribe}}\nThe Mech are found in both Assam and Bengal. Hodgson(1847) wrote as \"Mech is name imposed by strangers. This people call themselves as Bodo. Thus, Bodo is their proper designation\" They speak mainly the [[Bodo language]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Essay the first; On the Kocch, B\u00f3do and Dhim\u00e1l tribes|last=Hodgson|first=B.H.|publisher=J. Thomas|year=1847|isbn=|location=Calcutta|pages=105, 142, 154, 155, 156|quote=Mech is name imposed by strangers. This people call themselves as Bodo. Thus, Bodo is their proper designation}}</ref> J.D Anderson wrote, \"In Assam proper Hindus call them Kacharis, In Bengal they are known as Meches. Their own name for the race is Boro or Bodo.\"<ref>{{Harvcol|The Kacharis|J.D Anderson|p=xv}}</ref>\n\n===Dimasa===\n{{main|Dimasa people}}\nThe [[Kachari Kingdom|Kachari]] have a ruling clan among themselves who are termed as Bodosa. Some Dimasa scholars opined that they were also known as Bodosa at some point of time in History<ref>[http://shodhganga.inflibnet.ac.in/bitstream/10603/69516/7/07_chapter%202.pdf The Dimasa were known as Bodosa who migrated to Dimapur region and settled on the banks of Dhansiri, and later came to be known as Dimasa]</ref>\n\n===Chutiya-Burok===\n{{main|Chutiya people}}\nAmong [[Chutiya people|Chutias]], Burok means noble/great men. The Buroks formed a major part of the tribe. The Chutias who were thought to be healthy and strong was termed as Burok and took up the administrative and military roles in the Chutia kingdom. All Chutia royalty belonged to the Burok clan. Even the Motok king [[Sarbananada Singha|Sarbananda Singha]] belonged to the Burok Chutia clan.<ref>[http://atributetosankaradeva.org/mayamara.pdf Nath, D. ''The Mataks and their Revolt'', p.13]</ref> Surnames like Bora, Borha, Borua have their origins in the Chutia kingdom and are related to Bara/Bodo/Buruk only. There is mention of Manik Chandra Barua, Dhela Bora, Borhuloi Barua as commanders of Chutia army. Later the Ahoms adopted the title after the downfall of Chutias.<ref>Dr. Swarnalata Baruah(2004), ''Chutiya Jaatir Buranji'', Page 145, Surnames like Bora, Saikia, Kataki, Tamuli,etc. were found in Chutia kingdom. It is clearly stated in the Deodhai Buranji that when Ahom king Suhungmung attacked the Chutia kingdom on the banks of Dihing river, the Chutia army was led by one Manik Chandra Baruah. The surname \"Neog\" was probably derived from the Chutia \"Nayak\" whose duty was the same. Deori folklores also mention the myths behind the creation of each of these titles. For instance, \"Bora\" was said to be derived from the \"Buruk\" clan and acted either as a military official or a temple guard...</ref><ref>Dr. Swarnalata Baruah(2004), ''Chutiya Jaatir Buranji'', Page 129, The Chutia army was led by Borhuloi Borua and Dhela Bora.</ref>\n\n===Moran-Bodousa===\nThe Morans called their leader/chief as Bodousa (great son) where 'sa' means child or son in Moran language . The origin folklore of the Morans is same as that of Boruk Chutias which indicate that they were a faction which split at an early time.<ref>[http://shodhganga.inflibnet.ac.in/bitstream/10603/69486/9/09_chapter%202.pdf Moran chief Badaucha]</ref> They were also known as Habungiya or earth-folk or autochthones which means son of soil<ref>{{Harvcol|Endle|1911|p=88}}</ref>\n\n===Deori-Burok===\nThe Deoris (who were priests by profession) also have the Burok clan among them.\n\n===Twipuri-Borok===\nThe Tripuris often call themselves Boroks and their language is called Kokborok.<ref>[http://shodhganga.inflibnet.ac.in/bitstream/10603/69486/9/09_chapter%202.pdf Tripuris are called Boroks]</ref>\n\n===Reang-Bru===\nThe Reang people of Assam, Tripura and Mizoram call themselves Bru which means \"great men\".\n\n==Origins==\nThey were first classified by S. Endle as the Kacharis. They are considered to have reached the Brahmaputra valley via Tibet and South China, and settled in the foothills of the eastern Himalayan range which includes the whole of Assam, Tripura, North Bengal and parts of Bangladesh. That the Bodo-Kacharis were early colonizers of the river valleys is taken from the fact that most of the rivers in the Brahmaputra valley today carry Tibeto-Burman names \u2013 Dibang, Dihang, Dikhou, Dihing, etc. \u2013 where Di- means water in [[Bodo language|Bodo]]/Deori-Chutia, Moran, Dimasa, other dialects Bodo languages. (\"Ti\" in Lalung (Tiwa) language, \"Twi\" in Tripuri language, \"Dwi\" in 8th scheduled Boro & \"Chi\" in Garo). There are many places name given by Bodo-Kachari people are Dispur, Dinajpur, Dimapur, Dibrugarh, Hajo, Mongoldoi, Diphu etc.\n\n==Groups==\nBased on an 1881 census, there were 19 groups within the Kachari\nclassification:\n#[[Boro Tribe|Boro]]\n#[[Chutia people|Chutiya]]\n#[[Dhimal]]\n#[[Garo people|Garo]]\n#[[Hajong people|Hajong]]\n#[[Koch people|Koch]]\n#[[Lalung]] (Tiwa)\n# Mech\n#\tMoran\n#       Modahi\n#\tPhulgaria\n#[[Deuri people|Deuri]]\n#\t[[Rabha tribe|Rabha]]\n#\t[[Sonowal Kachari]]\n#\t[[Sarania kachari]]\n#\tSolaimiya\n#       [[Thengal Kachari]]\n#\t[[Tripuri people|Tiprasa]] \u2013 [[Bru Tribe |Bru]]([[Reang]]), Jamatia, Uchai, Noatia(Tripura), Debbarma, Murasing, Roaza, etc.\n\nSome of the groups, such as Moran and Sarania consider themselves as lower-caste Hindus. Other groups, such as the Garo, Rabha, Lalung (Tiwa) and Hajong having been isolated from the parental stock, have established separate identities. With the exception of the Garo, which is still a matrilineal society, the other groups have given up the rules of matrilineal society.\n\nThe Mech in Western Assam, the Boro in central Assam; the Dimasa in Dima Hasao district formerly North Cachar Hills, Nagaon district, Cachar district & Nagaland state and the Sonowal and Thengal in the eastern part of the Brahmaputra now represents the Kachari.\n\n==History==\nThe [[History of Tripura|Tripuri]], [[Chutiya Kingdom|Chutiya]], [[Koch dynasty|Koch-Mech]] and [[Kachari Kingdom|Kachari]] had established powerful kingdoms in the past. The Tripuri kings had even defeated the [[Mughal Empire|Mughal]]s and the [[Burma|Burmese]] kingdoms in the past. Today, the Bodos, the Tripuris, and the Garos have established a strong political and ethnic identity and are developing their language and literature. The Sonowal Kachari is also a branch of greater Kachari. They live in the districts of Dibrugarh, Tinsukia, Dhemaji, Sivasagar, Lakhimpur, Golaghat and Jorhat.\n\n===State formations of the Bodo-Kachari people===\nBodo-Kachari unitedly lived in [[Kamarupa|Kamarupa kingdom]] but Power struggle separated into many parts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://coochbehar.nic.in/HTMfiles/royal_history.html|title=Royal history of Cooch Behar|website=coochbehar.nic.in|access-date=2019-03-25}}</ref> {{Further|Koch dynasty|Chutiya Kingdom|Dimasa kingdom|Twipra Kingdom}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin|}}\n*{{Cite journal|last=Jacquesson|first=Fran\u00e7ois|date=2008|title=Discovering Boro-Garo|url=http://himalaya.socanth.cam.ac.uk/collections/journals/ebhr/pdf/EBHR_32_02.pdf|journal=History of an Analytical and Descriptive Linguistic Category|volume=|pages=|via=}}\n* {{Citation |url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=lC6FCZ9VcaAC&pg=PA73|last= Sharma |first=Chandan Kumar |contribution=Oral discourse and Bodo identity construction|editor-last=Muthukumaraswamy |editor-first=M.D. |title= Folklore as Discourse |pages=73\u201394|publisher=National folklore support centre|year=2006|isbn= 9788190148160 }}\n* {{cite thesis|ref=harv|type=PhD|first=Uttam|last=Bathari|title=Memory History and polity a study of dimasa identity in colonial past and post colonial present|publisher=Gauhati University|year=2014|degree=|doi=|hdl=10603/115353}}\n* {{cite thesis|ref=harv|type=PhD|first=Nirjay Kumar|last=Brahma|title=\tSocio political institutions in bodo society|publisher=Gauhati University|year=2008|degree=|doi=|hdl=10603/66535}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Burling|first=Robbins|pages=|chapter=The Tibeto-Burman Languages of Northeastern India|editor-last=LaPolla|editor-first=Randy J.|location=|author-link=Randy LaPolla|title=Sino-Tibetan languages|year=2013|isbn=|publisher=Routledge|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kYJFPZ34ihMC&lpg=PA3&pg=PT146#v=onepage&q&f=false}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Choudhury|first=Sujit|authorlink=|title=The Bodos: Emergence and Assertion of an ethnic minority|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K2YMAQAAMAAJ|accessdate=|year=2007|publisher=Indian Institute of Advanced Study|location=Shimla|isbn=9788179860540|page=|pages=}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Endle|first=Sidney|authorlink=|title=The Kacharis|url=https://archive.org/details/kacharis009491mbp|accessdate=20 February 2013|year=1911|publisher=Macmillan and Co.|location=London|isbn=|page=|pages=}}\n* {{cite journal|ref=harv|last1=Basu|first1=Analabha|year=2003|title=Ethnic India: A Genomic View, With Special Reference to Peopling and Structure|journal=Genome Research|volume=13|issue=10|pages=2277\u20132290|doi=10.1101/gr.1413403|pmid=14525929|pmc=403703}}\n* {{cite journal|ref=harv|last1=George|first1=Sudhir Jacob|year=1994|title=The Bodo Movement in Assam: Unrest to Accord|url=|journal=Asian Survey|publisher=University of California Press|pages=878\u2013892|volume=34|number=10|doi=10.1525/as.1994.34.10.00p0431w}}\n*{{Linguistic Survey of India|3|2}}\n* {{cite conference|ref=harv|via=|last=Mosahary|first=R N|authorlink=|title=The Boros : Their Origin, Migration and Settlement in Assam|book-title=Proceedings of Northeast India History Association|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701071648/http://dspace.nehu.ac.in/xmlui/bitstream/handle/1/11330/The%20boros%20(RN%20Mosahary).pdf|conference=|accessdate=2019-06-30|year=1983|publisher=Northeast India History Association|location=Barapani|isbn=|volume=|page=|pages=42\u201370}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Narjinari|first=Hira Charan|authorlink=|title=Reassertiveness of the Great Bodos|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=A1RuAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=|year=2000|publisher=|location=|isbn=|page=|pages=}}\n* {{cite book|pages=|ref=eighth|last=GoI|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|title=Eighth Scheduled Indian Languages|url=http://mha.nic.in/hindi/sites/upload_files/mhahindi/files/pdf/Eighth_Schedule.pdf|access-date=13 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305010536/http://mha.nic.in/hindi/sites/upload_files/mhahindi/files/pdf/Eighth_Schedule.pdf#|archive-date=5 March 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}\n*{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=4ba1AAAAIAAJ|title=The place of Assam in the history and civilisation of India |last=Chatterjee |first=S.K.|publisher= Guwahati University |year=1970|isbn=|location=|pages=}}\n{{refend}}\n{{Scheduled tribes of India}}\n{{Hill tribes of Northeast India}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kachari}}\n[[Category:Social groups of Assam]]\n[[Category:Tribes of Assam]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Northeast India]]\n[[Category:Scheduled Tribes of Meghalaya]]\n[[Category:Scheduled Tribes of Assam]]\n[[Category:Scheduled Tribes of Nagaland]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in South Asia]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|group of ethnic peoples|the specific ethnic group|Bodo people}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n| group = Bodo-Kachari Peoples\n| native_name = Kachari\n| image = File:Kherai Dance of Assam.jpg\n| image_caption = Boro Kherai Dance\n| population = [[Circa|c.]] '''12\u201314&nbsp;million'''\n| region1 = [[Assam]]\n| pop1 = n/a\n| region2 = [[Tripura]]\n| pop2 = n/a\n| region3 = [[Meghalaya]]\n| pop3 = n/a\n| region4 = [[Arunachal Pradesh]]\n| pop4 = n/a\n| rels = '''Predominant''' {{hlist|[[Hinduism]] }}\n'''Minority''' {{hlist| [[Christianity]]| [[Animism]]}}\n| related = {{hlist | other [[Tibeto-Burman]] groups}}\n| native_name_lang = \n| languages = \n}}\n{{Culture of Assam}}\n'''Bodo-Kachari''' (also '''Kachari''',{{sfn|Endle|1911}} '''Bodo'''<ref name=\"jacobnote\"/>) is a generic term applied to a number of [[ethnic group]]s living predominantly in the [[Northeast India]]n state of [[Assam]], that speak [[Assamese language|Assamese]] and [[Tibeto-Burman languages]] and possibly have a shared ancestry. Although most of these groups spoke different forms of [[Boro-Garo languages]] in historical times, today a majority of them speak Assamese. \n\nThe [[Bodo language]], one of the languages in the Boro-Garo group, has been recognised as an eighth scheduled Indian language since 2004. They are part of the [[Tibeto-Burman and Tai peoples of Assam|Tibeto-Burman speaking community]] of Assam.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Govt. of India|first1=Ministry of Home Affairs|title=Eight Schedules|url=http://mha.nic.in/hindi/sites/upload_files/mhahindi/files/pdf/Eighth_Schedule.pdf|website=mha.nic.in|access-date=13 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305010536/http://mha.nic.in/hindi/sites/upload_files/mhahindi/files/pdf/Eighth_Schedule.pdf#|archive-date=5 March 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThey are considered to have reached the Brahmaputra valley via Tibet and settled in the foothills of the eastern Himalayan range which includes the whole of Assam, Tripura, North Bengal and parts of Bangladesh. The belief that Bodo-Kacharis were early settlers of the river valleys is taken from the fact that most of the rivers in the Brahmaputra valley today carry Tibeto-Burman names\u2014Dibang, Dihang, Dikhou, Dihing, Doiyang, Doigrung etc.\u2014where ''Di/Doi-'' means water in Boro-Garo languages.\n\nSome of the groups, such as Moran and Saraniya consider themselves as lower-caste Hindus under [[Ekasarana Dharma]]. Other groups, such as the Garo, Rabha, Lalung and Hajong having been isolated from the parental stock, have established separate identities. With the exception of the Garo, which is still a matrilineal society, the other groups do not follow rules of matrilineal society.\n\nThe Mech in Western Assam, the Boro in central Assam; the Dimasa in Dima Hasao District (DHD) formerly North Cachar Hills, Cachar district and Nagaland state and the Sonowal and Thengal in the eastern part of the Brahmaputra now represent the Kachari.\n\n==Etymologies==\n===Bodo===\nThe term ''Bodo'' was published by [[Brian Houghton Hodgson|Hodgson]] in 1847, to denote the [[Mech tribe|Mech]] people of Darjeeling district and their language,<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{harv|Narjinari|2000|p=4}}{{harv|Grierson|1903|p=1}}</ref> though this term was never used in the sources of history of Assam.<ref>\"The term Bodo was first used by Brian H Hodgson in his book ''On the Koch, Bodo and Dhimal Tribes'' in 1847 and no reference of the term is seen in any sources in the history of Assam.\" {{harvcol|Bathari|2014|p=14}}</ref> [[George Abraham Grierson|Grierson]] took this term to denote a section of the Assam-Burma group of the [[Tibeto-Burman]] speakers of the [[Sino-Tibetan languages|Sino-Tibetan]] speech family,{{sfn|Choudhury|2007|p=1}} which included the languages of (1) Mech; (2) Rabha; (3) Lalung (Tiwa); (4) Dimasa (Hills Kachari); (5) Garo (6) Tiprasa and (7) Chutiya.{{sfn|Grierson|1903|p=2}} Over time, for anthropological and linguistic purposes, ''Bodo'' came to denote all people in Nepal, India, and Bangladesh that spoke related languages now or in the past, or claimed a shared ancestry.<ref>\"[I]t seems that the term Bodo is used particularly to denote sections of people having an agnatic relationship in terms of speech practices and a strong sense of shared ancestry. This term the Bodo is more anthropological in its usage.\" {{harvcol|Bathari|2014|p=14}}</ref> This umbrella-group includes such sub-groups as Mech in Bengal and Nepal; Boros (also confusingly called Bodo), Dimasa, Chutia, Sonowal, Rabha, Tiwa in Assam, and the Kokborok people in Tripura and Bangladesh.<ref>{{harvcol|Bathari|2014|p=14}}</ref><ref name=\"jacobnote\">\"The term Bodo is also used to denote a large number of tribes&mdash; The Bodo people, The Garos of Meghalaya, Tiprasa of Tripura, Koch, Rabha, Lalung, Dimasa, Hajong, Chutia, Deuri and Moran of Assam and other parts of Northeast (M N Brahma, \"The Bodo-Kacharis of Assam---A brief Introduction) 1:1 (1983) p52\" {{harv|George|1994|p=878}}</ref> This is in contrast to popular and socio-political usage, where Bodo denotes the politically dominant sub-group\u2014the ''Boros''\u2014in the [[Bodoland|Bodoland Territorial Autonomous Districts]].<ref>\"In present-day socio-political terminology, the Bodo means the plains tribes of the Brahmaputra Valley known earlier as Bodo-Kachari.\" {{harv|Choudhury|2007|p=1}}</ref><ref>\"The media at the regional and national level; officials at the Centre and the state political parties of all hues and the people, in general, have accepted what may be termed as a contraction of the original denotion.\" {{harv|Choudhury|2007|p=1}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the word \"Bodo\" was used as an umbrella term during the British period, the term generally stands for ''man'' in some of the cognate languages (Boro:''Boro''; Tripuri:''Borok'') but not in others (Garo:''Mande''; Karbi:''Arlen'').<ref>\"One section of the same stock, Garo, a Tribe called themselves \u201cMande\u201d means Man: another word Arleng (Karbi) is popularly used among Karbis, which literally means Man.\" {{harvcol|Brahma|2008|pp=1\u20132}}</ref>  According to historians, the word \"Bodo\" is derived from the Tibetan ''Hbrogpa''.<ref>\"The inception of the term 'Boro' may be traced from a Tibetan word 'Hbrogpa' an inhabitant of steppes belongs to Mongolean race.\" {{harvcol|Brahma|2008|p=2}}</ref>\n\nThe umbrella name \"Bodo\" is resisted by numerically smaller groups such as the Dimasas.<ref>This has been viewed with contempt by several sections of the groups as a design by the Boros to establish their pre-dominance over numerically and otherwise weaker sections of the group. Most of the resistance has come from the Dimasas, who often accuse the Boros of appropriating the history and language of the Dimasas.{{harv|Bathari|2014|p=14-15}}</ref>\n\n===Kachari===\nOn the other hand, the term ''Kachari'' has been used through much of history to denote the same people.<ref>\"On the other hand, for the larger part of history, this group of people is referred to as Kacharis.\" {{harvcol|Bathari|2014|p=14}}</ref> One of the earliest usage can be found in the 16-th century [[Assamese language]] [[Bhagavat of Sankardev|Bhagavata]].<ref>Srimandbhagavat, skandha 2, H Dattabaruah and Co., Nalbari, pp-38: ''kiraTa kachhaari khaachi gaaro miri'' / ''yavana ka~Nka govaala'' /</ref>\nKachari is pronounced as Kachh\u0101ri or Koss\u0101ri. The origin of the name is most likely a self-designation ''korosa aris'' that is found in a very old Kachari song:<ref>{{harvcol|Mosahary|1983|p=47}}</ref>\n<poem>\n''Pra Ari, Korasa Ari''\n''Jong pari lari lari''\n(We are Korosa Aris, first-born sea race\nOur line is continuous)\n</poem>\n\n==Ethnic groups==\n\n=== Boro ===\n{{main|Boro people}}\nThe Boro people, also called Bodo, are found concentrated in the [[duars]] regions, north of [[Goalpara]] and [[Kamrup region|Kamrup]]. The origin of Kachari term was unknown to Boro themselves, but known to others. They call themselves as Boro, Bada, Bodo, Barafisa. Barafisa translated as Children of the Bara.\n\n===Mech===\n{{main|Mech tribe}}\nThe Mech are found in both Assam and Bengal. Hodgson(1847) wrote as \"Mech is name imposed by strangers. This people call themselves as Bodo. Thus, Bodo is their proper designation\" They speak mainly the [[Bodo language]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Essay the first; On the Kocch, B\u00f3do and Dhim\u00e1l tribes|last=Hodgson|first=B.H.|publisher=J. Thomas|year=1847|isbn=|location=Calcutta|pages=105, 142, 154, 155, 156|quote=Mech is name imposed by strangers. This people call themselves as Bodo. Thus, Bodo is their proper designation}}</ref> J.D Anderson wrote, \"In Assam proper Hindus call them Kacharis, In Bengal they are known as Meches. Their own name for the race is Boro or Bodo.\"<ref>{{Harvcol|The Kacharis|J.D Anderson|p=xv}}</ref>\n\n===Dimasa===\n{{main|Dimasa people}}\nThe [[Kachari Kingdom|Kachari]] have a ruling clan among themselves who are termed as Bodosa. Some Dimasa scholars opined that they were also known as Bodosa at some point of time in History<ref>[http://shodhganga.inflibnet.ac.in/bitstream/10603/69516/7/07_chapter%202.pdf The Dimasa were known as Bodosa who migrated to Dimapur region and settled on the banks of Dhansiri, and later came to be known as Dimasa]</ref>\n\n===Chutiya-Burok===\n{{main|Chutiya people}}\nAmong [[Chutiya people|Chutias]], Burok means noble/great men. The Buroks formed a major part of the tribe. The Chutias who were thought to be healthy and strong was termed as Burok and took up the administrative and military roles in the Chutia kingdom. All Chutia royalty belonged to the Burok clan. Even the Motok king [[Sarbananada Singha|Sarbananda Singha]] belonged to the Burok Chutia clan.<ref>[http://atributetosankaradeva.org/mayamara.pdf Nath, D. ''The Mataks and their Revolt'', p.13]</ref> Surnames like Bora, Borha, Borua have their origins in the Chutia kingdom and are related to Bara/Bodo/Buruk only. There is mention of Manik Chandra Barua, Dhela Bora, Borhuloi Barua as commanders of Chutia army. Later the Ahoms adopted the title after the downfall of Chutias.<ref>Dr. Swarnalata Baruah(2004), ''Chutiya Jaatir Buranji'', Page 145, Surnames like Bora, Saikia, Kataki, Tamuli,etc. were found in Chutia kingdom. It is clearly stated in the Deodhai Buranji that when Ahom king Suhungmung attacked the Chutia kingdom on the banks of Dihing river, the Chutia army was led by one Manik Chandra Baruah. The surname \"Neog\" was probably derived from the Chutia \"Nayak\" whose duty was the same. Deori folklores also mention the myths behind the creation of each of these titles. For instance, \"Bora\" was said to be derived from the \"Buruk\" clan and acted either as a military official or a temple guard...</ref><ref>Dr. Swarnalata Baruah(2004), ''Chutiya Jaatir Buranji'', Page 129, The Chutia army was led by Borhuloi Borua and Dhela Bora.</ref>\n\n===Moran-Bodousa===\nThe Morans called their leader/chief as Bodousa (great son) where 'sa' means child or son in Moran language . The origin folklore of the Morans is same as that of Boruk Chutias which indicate that they were a faction which split at an early time.<ref>[http://shodhganga.inflibnet.ac.in/bitstream/10603/69486/9/09_chapter%202.pdf Moran chief Badaucha]</ref> They were also known as Habungiya or earth-folk or autochthones which means son of soil<ref>{{Harvcol|Endle|1911|p=88}}</ref>\n\n===Deori-Burok===\nThe Deoris (who were priests by profession) also have the Burok clan among them.\n\n===Twipuri-Borok===\nThe Tripuris often call themselves Boroks and their language is called Kokborok.<ref>[http://shodhganga.inflibnet.ac.in/bitstream/10603/69486/9/09_chapter%202.pdf Tripuris are called Boroks]</ref>\n\n===Reang-Bru===\nThe Reang people of Assam, Tripura and Mizoram call themselves Bru which means \"great men\".\n\n==Origins==\nThey were first classified by S. Endle as the Kacharis. They are considered to have reached the Brahmaputra valley via Tibet and South China, and settled in the foothills of the eastern Himalayan range which includes the whole of Assam, Tripura, North Bengal and parts of Bangladesh. That the Bodo-Kacharis were early colonizers of the river valleys is taken from the fact that most of the rivers in the Brahmaputra valley today carry Tibeto-Burman names \u2014 Dibang, Dihang, Dikhou, Dihing, etc. \u2014 where Di- means water in [[Bodo language|Bodo]]/Deori-Chutia, Moran, Dimasa, other dialects Bodo languages. (\"Ti\" in Lalung (Tiwa) language, \"Twi\" in Tripuri language, \"Dwi\" in 8th scheduled Boro & \"Chi\" in Garo). There are many places name given by Bodo-Kachari people are Dispur, Dinajpur, Dimapur, Dibrugarh, Hajo, Mongoldoi, Diphu etc.\n\n==Groups==\nBased on an 1881 census, there were 19 groups within the Kachari\nclassification:\n#[[Boro Tribe|Boro]]\n#[[Chutia people|Chutiya]]\n#[[Dhimal]]\n#[[Garo people|Garo]]\n#[[Hajong people|Hajong]]\n#[[Koch people|Koch]]\n#[[Lalung]] (Tiwa)\n# Mech\n#\tMoran\n#       Modahi\n#\tPhulgaria\n#[[Deuri people|Deuri]]\n#\t[[Rabha tribe|Rabha]]\n#\t[[Sonowal Kachari]]\n#\t[[Sarania kachari|Sarania Kachari]]\n#\tSolaimiya\n#       [[Thengal Kachari]]\n#\t[[Tripuri people|Tiprasa]] \u2013 [[Bru Tribe |Bru]]([[Reang]]), Jamatia, Uchai, Noatia(Tripura), Debbarma, Murasing, Roaza, etc.\n\nSome of the groups, such as Moran and Sarania consider themselves as lower-caste Hindus. Other groups, such as the Garo, Rabha, Lalung (Tiwa) and Hajong having been isolated from the parental stock, have established separate identities. With the exception of the Garo, which is still a matrilineal society, the other groups have given up the rules of matrilineal society.\n\nThe Mech in Western Assam, the Boro in central Assam; the Dimasa in Dima Hasao district formerly North Cachar Hills, Nagaon district, Cachar district & Nagaland state and the Sonowal and Thengal in the eastern part of the Brahmaputra now represents the Kachari.\n\n==History==\nThe [[History of Tripura|Tripuri]], [[Chutiya Kingdom|Chutiya]], [[Koch dynasty|Koch-Mech]] and [[Kachari Kingdom|Kachari]] had established powerful kingdoms in the past. The Tripuri kings had even defeated the [[Mughal Empire|Mughal]]s and the [[Burma|Burmese]] kingdoms in the past. Today, the Bodos, the Tripuris, and the Garos have established a strong political and ethnic identity and are developing their language and literature. The Sonowal Kachari is also a branch of greater Kachari. They live in the districts of Dibrugarh, Tinsukia, Dhemaji, Sivasagar, Lakhimpur, Golaghat and Jorhat.\n\n===State formations of the Bodo-Kachari people===\nBodo-Kachari unitedly lived in [[Kamarupa|Kamarupa kingdom]] but Power struggle separated into many parts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://coochbehar.nic.in/HTMfiles/royal_history.html|title=Royal history of Cooch Behar|website=coochbehar.nic.in|access-date=2019-03-25}}</ref> {{Further|Koch dynasty|Chutiya Kingdom|Dimasa kingdom|Twipra Kingdom}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin|}}\n*{{Cite journal|last=Jacquesson|first=Fran\u00e7ois|date=2008|title=Discovering Boro-Garo|url=http://himalaya.socanth.cam.ac.uk/collections/journals/ebhr/pdf/EBHR_32_02.pdf|journal=History of an Analytical and Descriptive Linguistic Category|volume=|pages=|via=}}\n* {{Citation |url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=lC6FCZ9VcaAC&pg=PA73|last= Sharma |first=Chandan Kumar |contribution=Oral discourse and Bodo identity construction|editor-last=Muthukumaraswamy |editor-first=M.D. |title= Folklore as Discourse |pages=73\u201394|publisher=National folklore support centre|year=2006|isbn= 9788190148160 }}\n* {{cite thesis|ref=harv|type=Ph.D.|first=Uttam|last=Bathari|title=Memory History and polity a study of dimasa identity in colonial past and post colonial present|publisher=Gauhati University|year=2014|degree=|doi=|hdl=10603/115353}}\n* {{cite thesis|ref=harv|type=Ph.D.|first=Nirjay Kumar|last=Brahma|title=\tSocio political institutions in bodo society|publisher=Gauhati University|year=2008|degree=|doi=|hdl=10603/66535}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Burling|first=Robbins|pages=|chapter=The Tibeto-Burman Languages of Northeastern India|editor-last=LaPolla|editor-first=Randy J.|location=|author-link=Randy LaPolla|title=Sino-Tibetan languages|year=2013|isbn=|publisher=Routledge|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kYJFPZ34ihMC&lpg=PA3&pg